INSERT INTO `wp_comments` VALUES (2,115,'Tal Serphos','tserphos@gmail.com','http://backfeed.cc','109.160.133.46','2015-11-18 10:35:00','2015-11-18 10:35:00','Following comments on twitter by @cdetrio\n\n\n\nWhen you offer Schelling game I assume you are meaning many \"calculators\" provide their answer together with a deposit, and the right answer will be the answer into which the highest amount of deposit was attached to?\n\nThe problem with verifying calculations (that cannot be verified on-chain) in this manner is that for the Schelling game to work I think you need to have everyone calculating every calculation up for reward. Otherwise an attacker will be able to provide enough deposit for almost every single calculation and make the contract accept a wrong answer (as well as \"steal\" the deposit from all those giving the correct answer).\nI still don\'t have a good scheme for this case, Ethereum is supposed to be Turing complete I am not sure this will be necessary.\nRegarding the use of bounties for easily verifiable solutions - why use them instead of allowing each calculating node to state its fee? the varying fee actually allows for the batch auction mechanism you suggested, and without it it\'s just a matter of the \"highest deposit takes it all\".',0,'1','Disqus/1.1(2.84):2365978660','',0,0),(3,115,'Rick Dudley','a.frederick.dudley@gmail.com','','66.108.90.177','2015-11-19 02:16:00','2015-11-19 02:16:00','Just to be clear, I am sure this system will work in the sense that code will execute. I am also sure that someone will have some computation that fits well into this model. My main point of confusion is it seems to be creating another model of trust where a computation that would be financially less expensive to run off-chain is being solicited on-chain and run off-chain, but without verification. (So why use the chain at all?)\n\nIf the cost of \"optional\" verification is the cost of doing the computation on-chain, it is surely cheaper in terms of dollars to simply do the computation off-chain.\n\nIf the cost of verification is significantly less than the cost of computation then verification should happen automatically, but the solicitor would still be paying a premium for the off-chain computation.\n\nThere are a lot of different ways of looking at this but the point I am making is that:\nsolicitation + off-chain computation + (optional)verification + hand wavy value of reputation and quasi-verification &lt; just using an oracle and having a reputation.\n\nI am sure that there are cases where the above equation must be true, and there might be a computation like ring signatures, that will be done this way en masse, but it doesn&#039;t seem like a general solution in the slightest, because the pricing of the computation and the risk associated with it is nontrivial.',0,'1','Disqus/1.1(2.84):2367502684','',0,0),(4,115,'Tal Serphos','tserphos@gmail.com','http://backfeed.cc','199.203.151.209','2015-11-19 10:38:00','2015-11-19 10:38:00','I think you missed an important point Rick. There is no trust in the market scheme I am offering, imagine this scenario:\n\nBob (a contract) offers a calculation to be made, which can verified by an on-chain calculation together with a minimum deposit (significantly higher then the sum needed to run the computation on-chain) and maximum deposit return time (X blocks - should be enough to run the required calculation on-chain).\n\nI am one out of unlimited amount of nodes offering to calculate the needed calculation offline by submitting the result to bob together with the heavy deposit and my requested fee.\n\nbob will look at all the incoming results. If a deposit is smaller then the minimum amount - it is ignored. \n\nNow:\n\n1. If all the results are the same then the lowest requested fee wins and gets the fee.\n\n2. If they are different (at least 1 different) - then the calculation is run on-chain and the true result is achieved. Now:\n\n2.a If no one gave the correct result - all deposits go to bob (they sum to more of the calculation cost, so bob just got compensated for waiting a little for the results before running the calculation) \n2.b if some nodes gave the correct result: they share the deposits made by all the wrong nodes - the calculation cost that goes to bob (so bob still got compensated for the small waiting time)\n\nSo When I consider what to do - I can either:\n\n1. Really calculate the calculation and compete on the fee together with all other truthful nodes - in which case I get a chance to get a fee for my work, or better - get the deposits of lying nodes\n\n2. Risk it and don\'t make the calculation, only send a random result and hope that no one will send a result. but here even one other truthful sends the correct result I will pay heavily by losing my deposit.\n\nSo there is no need for trust here as the economic incentive of each node is to be truthful. Sending wrong answers has it\'s penalties.\n\nThe natural state this system will find itself in is many truthful nodes just competing on getting the fee (allowing for lower fees).\n\nI don\'t need to verify anything (nodes verify each other) and I don\'t need to trust an Oracle (all nodes are oracles).\n\nThere are many other nice aspects to this model - for example the need to put an upfront deposit prevents one player of taking over the market (as a centralized Oracle service can) and allows anyone to join the game.\n\nA downside of this peer verification method is the inability to introduce randomness into the calculations, since results are verified by comparing them to peer results.',0,'1','Disqus/1.1(2.84):2367914329','',3,0),(5,115,'Tal Serphos','tserphos@gmail.com','http://backfeed.cc','199.203.151.209','2015-11-19 10:44:00','2015-11-19 10:44:00','You can dive deeper into this \"economic consensus\" scheme by watching Vlad Zamfir\'s talk at Devcon1. It was the second talk on Monday, and the videos from Monday are not up yet, so in the meantime you can go over the slides here:\nhttps://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1biPBVqCgV1WqJjUw0ZkOgPHVCmmqXdtrbImgXSdSTSA/edit',0,'1','Disqus/1.1(2.84):2367919208','',3,0),(6,115,'Rick Dudley','a.frederick.dudley@gmail.com','','66.108.90.177','2015-11-19 11:36:00','2015-11-19 11:36:00','TL;DR It\'s difficult to make system like this work because transactions on Ethereum are interdependent which makes it basically impossible for Bob to set a price on the deposit that will discourage Chuck from DoSing.\n\nThanks, this is a much better explanation, but there are still some issues:\n\"There is no trust in the market scheme I am offering[...]\"\nClearly you are assuming the economic rationality of a potential attacker (named Chuck), which I think is incorrect because the VALUE of the solicited calculation to at least one of the counterparties must be greater than their COST or else the calculation would not happen in the first place. But also, the net cost and net value have to be taken into consideration when considering the value gained from an attack which is targeting not the calculation itself but Bob\'s counterparty (named Alice).\n\nCongruently, you\'re assuming that Bob knows the value Chuck will gain by DoSing the calculation and that Bob can afford to price that into the deposit, such that Chuck participates honestly instead of DoSing. I don\'t see how Bob will ever have enough information to do this. Or put another way: The value Bob gains from the transaction must be greater than the sum to run the calculation on-chain, or else the transaction just won\'t happen. But in order for your system to work reliably Bob\'s deposit must not just be greater than the cost of on-chain calculation, it must also be greater than the net value of the transaction to be DoS resistant.\n\nBecause of the relationship between the deposits and the net value, we can\'t say how much value will be gained by Chuck. Because Chuck might be a counterparty to Alice in some other transaction we can\'t say when it will be economically rational for Chuck to DoS, which can be done trivially by simply mutating the first response seen. \n\nAgain, I am sure there are times when all of this aligns as you wish, but it is entirely unclear to me, based my understanding of your analysis, which outcome is more likely for a general calculation, the DoSed case or the \"allowed\" case.',0,'1','Disqus/1.1(2.84):2367965465','',4,0),(7,115,'Rick Dudley','a.frederick.dudley@gmail.com','','66.108.90.177','2015-11-19 14:23:00','2015-11-19 14:23:00','I have spoken with Vlad and raised my concerns with him already. His arguments don\'t address the point I am making above. :D\n\nIt\'s also worth mentioning that behavioral economics and neuroeconomics are both based around the assumption that in fact economic actors are not rational. I\'m not sure why we rely on a random 20-something as our source for contemporary economics (or psychology). :D',0,'1','Disqus/1.1(2.84):2368159889','',5,0),(8,115,'Rick Dudley','a.frederick.dudley@gmail.com','','66.108.90.177','2015-11-19 14:40:00','2015-11-19 14:40:00','If you read about cheaters, you find plenty of evidence that \"economic consensus\" simply doesn\'t have the properties Vlad claims it does. Here is an example: http://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2015/11/scottish-man-indicted-for-twitter-based-stock-fraud/',0,'1','Disqus/1.1(2.84):2368184260','',5,0),(9,115,'Tal Serphos','tserphos@gmail.com','http://backfeed.cc','199.203.151.209','2015-11-19 19:28:00','2015-11-19 19:28:00','But this is a totally different case. \nThe economic consensus Vlad is talking has nothing to do with the assumption of rational behavior. In free markets - there is no \"real price\" so you count on rational behavior and if you cheat you might get away with it. For the calculation market there is a real result - set by the calculation done on the Ethereum computer, so you cannot cheat as you will always get caught and pay the price for it. The only chance you have is if no one else submits the correct answer..\nIt\'s like trying to cheat in poker where your hand is open and hope that the other players wouldn\'t watch the cards..',0,'1','Disqus/1.1(2.84):2368723512','',8,0),(10,115,'Tal Serphos','tserphos@gmail.com','http://backfeed.cc','199.203.151.209','2015-11-19 19:37:00','2015-11-19 19:37:00','I think I am missing something here. Who do you expect chuck to DoS? a specific counter-party to bob? but bob will probably receive a large number of responses from many parties, previously unknown to chuck..',0,'1','Disqus/1.1(2.84):2368737361','',6,0),(11,115,'Rick Dudley','a.frederick.dudley@gmail.com','','66.108.90.177','2015-11-19 20:41:00','2015-11-19 20:41:00','This is not a substantive reply to my critique. I provided a quite detailed argument for why you system will have really difficult to reason about failure modes. \n\nAs I mentioned previously, your pricing strategy must be flawed because an \"external\" price that Bob cannot have knowledge of is what will motivate Chuck.\n\nI\'m sure everything will work out for the best. :D\n\nI guess I should also point out, the solution to all of this is to just use a collection of oracles, i\'m pretty sure Augur and Groupnosis get off-chain truth in similar ways. There are number of descriptions of these types of systems available.\n\nThe only point I was trying to make was that if you try to make truth exclusively intrinsic to the Ethereum Network, the public interdependency of transactions makes modeling the risk far more complex than what you\'re suggesting.',0,'1','Disqus/1.1(2.84):2368849410','',9,0),(12,115,'Casey Detrio','cdetrio@gmail.com','','84.253.54.151','2015-11-22 07:55:00','2015-11-22 07:55:00','&gt; for the Schelling game to work I think you need to have everyone [...] Otherwise an attacker [...]\n\nYeah, Schelling coordination games have relatively fragile equilibria (case in point: bitcoin\'s &gt; 51% honest hashpower requirement). But they\'re the only decentralized mechanism we have for answers/resolutions that that can\'t be objectively verified.\n\n&gt; Regarding the use of bounties for easily verifiable solutions - why use them instead of allowing each calculating node to state its fee?\n\nOh hmm.. come to think of it, having the contract offer a specific bounty is a posted-price market, whereas having the calculating nodes state their fees is an auction market. So you\'re right, a fee auction market can do the same thing (and might be preferable).\n\nMy main point was that if the problem is efficiently-verifiable, then you don\'t need to code the actual calculation in ethereum script; only the verification routine needs to be coded and executed on-chain.\n\nbtw, thanks for the shoutout!\n',0,'1','Disqus/1.1(2.84):2372827992','',2,0),(13,115,'Tal Serphos','tserphos@gmail.com','http://backfeed.cc','212.29.222.36','2015-11-22 08:03:00','2015-11-22 08:03:00','Your\'e welcome. And a good point.',0,'1','Disqus/1.1(2.84):2372831863','',12,0),(14,115,'Casey Detrio','cdetrio@gmail.com','','84.253.54.151','2015-11-22 08:08:00','2015-11-22 08:08:00','&gt; My main point of confusion is it seems to be creating another model of trust where a computation that would be financially less expensive to run off-chain is being solicited on-chain and run off-chain, but without verification. (So why use the chain at all?)\n\nThe chain is being used here for off-chain computation in a manner quite similar to how it is used in micropayment channels (Lightning Network etc.) for off-chain transactions. The \"threat\" of being able to use on-chain calculations to resolve disputes is what keeps the off-chain parties honest. That means the service is still essentially trustless (whereas oracles and reputation are not).',0,'1','Disqus/1.1(2.84):2372834708','',3,0),(15,115,'Rick Dudley','a.frederick.dudley@gmail.com','','66.108.90.177','2015-11-22 09:05:00','2015-11-22 09:05:00','Sorry, you\'re right what I wrote before is confusing.\n\nAlice is a counterparty to Bob but is not participating in the off-chain computation. Alice is consuming a result from the off-chain computation. Chuck is attacking Alice by DoSing the computation that Bob provides to Alice. I think the best way to move forward from here is try to DoS Bob as Chuck, it\'s trivial to do... I explain the fix above. Basically, all that rational actor stuff I\'ve discussed results in the locking model for challenges in your system being broken; anyone can force Bob to run the computation on-chain, and they have an open set of reasons to do so.\n\nIn the ask-bid system I explain above, the only entities that can lie to Bob are those that have already placed asks and fulfill Bob\'s constraints. This does not completely eliminate my original attack, but it makes modeling the risk significantly easier.\n\nDepending on how the constraints are defined, Bob may choose to never run the computation on-chain for verification and instead require n number of agreements before paying the participants. (Without reputation, this can still be attacked fairly easy by a quick Sybil, but whatever...)',0,'1','Disqus/1.1(2.84):2372863575','',10,0),(16,115,'Rick Dudley','a.frederick.dudley@gmail.com','','66.108.90.177','2015-11-22 09:10:00','2015-11-22 09:10:00','\"The chain is being used here for off-chain computation in a manner quite similar to how it is used in micropayment channels (Lightning Network etc.) for off-chain transactions.\"\nNope, the nature and order of the binding in Lightning is different, and that\'s the main issue.\n\nAn ask-bid exchange where the askers bond first and are providing the computation is the easiest way to do this. Then Bob places a bid which contains a reward and a set of constraints. If Bob only accepts asks that were posted before his bid, he cannot be DoSed. Bob can later post a challenge to a transaction and get part of the bond from the bad asker. (Some of the bond is destroyed, and maybe some is kept by the exchange.)',0,'1','Disqus/1.1(2.84):2372866441','',14,0),(17,115,'Casey Detrio','cdetrio@gmail.com','','84.253.54.151','2015-11-22 10:54:00','2015-11-22 10:54:00','&gt; basically impossible for Bob to set a price on the deposit that will discourage Chuck from DoSing.\n\nThe deposit is the amount required to pay the gas fees to run the computation on-chain (plus a bit more, to provide a reward for a challenger).\n\n&gt; anyone can force Bob to run the computation on-chain, and they have an open set of reasons to do so.\n\nSo what? This only means that anyone can DoS the computation for a block or two; to do so, an attacker will have to pay the gas fees required to run the computation on-chain.\n\n&gt; In the ask-bid system I explain above, the only entities that can lie to Bob are those that have already placed asks\n\nI dont see how this is different from the OP. The \"asks\" are the deposits placed by computing nodes.',0,'1','Disqus/1.1(2.84):2372930441','',15,0),(18,115,'Rick Dudley','a.frederick.dudley@gmail.com','','66.108.90.177','2015-11-22 17:52:00','2015-11-22 17:52:00','\"So what? This only means that anyone can DoS the computation for a block or two; to do so, an attacker will have to pay the gas fees required to run the computation on-chain.\"\n\nWe can have a system with a DoS vulnerability, or not. I rather minimize that risk.\n\n\"I dont see how this is different from the OP. The \"asks\" are the deposits placed by computing nodes.\"\n\nAs I have explained multiple times at this point, the order of the events has an impact on the attack surface, which should be obvious to anyone designing secure protocols.',0,'1','Disqus/1.1(2.84):2373365609','',17,0),(19,146,'Alex','Seldoon182@hotmail.com','http://www.daboloskov.com/','82.241.108.146','2016-01-21 21:10:00','2016-01-21 21:10:00','I don\'t understand... Which blockchain are you talking about ? Are you trusting whatever the protocole even if you don\'t know about technical background? Seriously...',0,'1','Disqus/1.1(2.84):2470686262','',0,0),(20,121,'Alex','Seldoon182@hotmail.com','http://www.daboloskov.com/','82.241.108.146','2016-01-21 21:17:00','2016-01-21 21:17:00','Once again I do agree on decentralized governance but talking about blockchain sounds like talking about the information highway. And the only used information highway used today is Bitcoin...',0,'1','Disqus/1.1(2.84):2470699309','',0,0),(21,116,'Alex','Seldoon182@hotmail.com','http://www.daboloskov.com/','82.241.108.146','2016-01-21 21:27:00','2016-01-21 21:27:00','I\'m sorry to be arch but that reputation system sucks as hell. You guy need to get in known with work from Francis Galton by example which explained the bias variance dilemma also called the wisdom of crowds. The lasted best example which show how the masses can be right is the Twitch Pokemon experience. Criticisms is easy art difficult but your protocole needs more work imao.',0,'1','Disqus/1.1(2.84):2470716231','',0,0),(22,120,'herbstephens','herbstephens@gmail.com','','71.202.223.62','2016-01-22 16:49:00','2016-01-22 16:49:00','Agree, but SO long-winded! In essence: digital currency is the new equity. Period. Nothing else new here!',0,'1','Disqus/1.1(2.84):2472045734','',0,0),(23,116,'Christina Bowen','sagecbowen@gmail.com','','66.228.23.111','2016-01-23 06:53:00','2016-01-23 06:53:00','@Alex. Perhaps you miss the point? The bias variance dilemma seems to me to say that simple rules (stigmergy?) are adept for solving complex problems, b/c too much detail in the picture of what is going on can introduce noise to cloud the systemic patterns, which is in line with what I understand of Backfeed.   Backfeed strikes me as more like peer-review in science than wild and rampant masses creating an idiocracy.  \n\n(see Stigmergic Economy And Large-Scale, Decentralized Networks - by Backfeed founder Matan Field https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LPE7Z9Fu5Nc )',0,'1','Disqus/1.1(2.84):2473237322','',21,0),(24,120,'Backfeed','backfeed@backfeed.cc','','199.203.151.209','2016-01-24 08:58:00','2016-01-24 08:58:00','Hi Denis.\nEverything we do is open source and creative commons.\nyou can check us out on GitHub - https://github.com/backfeed\n',0,'1','Disqus/1.1(2.84):2474772998','',0,0),(25,120,'Backfeed','backfeed@backfeed.cc','','199.203.151.209','2016-01-24 09:02:00','2016-01-24 09:02:00','well, we\'re glad that you agree :)',0,'1','Disqus/1.1(2.84):2474774913','',22,0),(26,120,'The Backfeed Economic Model for a Decentralized...','','http://www.scoop.it/t/daos/p/4058725945/2016/01/24/the-backfeed-economic-model-for-a-decentralized-age','185.82.148.10','2016-01-24 19:52:02','2016-01-24 19:52:02','[&#8230;] Intro: The Backfeed Protocol with its Proof-of-Value (PoV) algorithm, reputation system and token mechanism, provides a comprehensive social operating system for decentralized organisations and col&hellip;&nbsp; [&#8230;]',0,'1','Mozilla/5.0 (Windows; U; Windows NT 6.1; fr; rv:1.9.0.6) Gecko/2009011913 Firefox/3.0.6','pingback',0,0),(27,324,'How To Slowly Lose Control: Decentralization Ex...','','http://www.scoop.it/t/impact-investing-money-meaning/p/4059026956/2016/01/30/how-to-slowly-lose-control-decentralization-experiment-2-backfeed-magazine','185.82.148.10','2016-01-30 19:35:10','2016-01-30 19:35:10','[&#8230;] This article by Francesca Pick is republished from OuiShare Magazine This is the second of an article series documenting the OuiShare Fest decentralization experiment. Decentralizing a project is easier said than done. But no matter what, it will teach you a lot about your psyche, group dynamics and the value system of your team. When we met with &hellip;&nbsp; [&#8230;]',0,'1','Mozilla/5.0 (Windows; U; Windows NT 6.1; fr; rv:1.9.0.6) Gecko/2009011913 Firefox/3.0.6','pingback',0,0),(28,332,'&quot;A Call for Decentralized Governance&quot;: On the Lack of Democracy in Bitcoin | P2P Foundation','','http://blog.p2pfoundation.net/a-call-for-decentralized-governance-on-the-lack-of-democracy-in-bitcoin/2016/02/01','64.34.184.28','2016-