er. Sure, a skilled plumber can fix a leaking pipe better than a philosophy student, but in two months of fixing leaking pipes, the philosophy student </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">is</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> a skilled plumber. Every member learns new skills, takes on new jobs—there are no hurdles in the way, other tha\r\nn willingness and competence. Sometimes people try a job and realize after a while that they don\'t like it, so they stop. Most members want variety in their work lives so no one chooses to do forty hours of the same job. Most members eventually sculpt a work life that is challenging, fulfilling, and rewarding.\r\n</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">In the mainstream, individuals claim to pursue education as a path to a more fulfilling life. What common threads of a fulfilling life should education be concerned with providing? Perhaps these: satisfying work, intellectual challenge, being of use, adequate pay. That is the implicit deal that higher education offers: sacrifice your childhood and young adulthood to us and in return your education will open the doors to a better, more bountiful, more challenging future. That is a promise that is increasingly broken.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Teenagers, intent on finding a career, must first gather all the credentials for that career before getting a chance to even see if they are suited to that work, but once they go through the time and expense to get the credentials, they are pretty well stuck with that career, whether they like it or not. Consequently, millions of people are in jobs that are other than they anticipated—lesser, worse—with no easy option for going back to square one and getting re-credentialed for another, more engaging career. After all, </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">this</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> job was worse than expected, the next could prove just as disappointing. One of the fastest growing segments of the student body at community colleges is people who already have a four-year degree and return to get a marketable skill. </span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">College serves another purpose—a purpose colleges don\'t mention in their course catalog— colleges habituate young people to accept a mismatch between form and content, official representations and reality. The passing of examinations, meeting of course deadlines, and disciplined study for the sake of mastering a body of knowledge demonstrates a willingness to conform to organizational discipline and displays the disposition needed to develop competence in a bureaucracy. Intellectuals pursue an academic career to become professionalized and this professionalization leads people not to higher intellectual rigor, but to stop thinking. The corporate world deals in abstractions, true, but trafficking in abstractions is not the same as thinking.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">White-collar professions have been routinized and degraded: standardized tests remove a teacher\'s discretion in the curriculum; strict sentencing guidelines prevent a judge from judging. Efforts of managers are not toward some tangible outcome. </span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The desire of hum<img class=\"wp-image-416 alignright\" src=\"http://magazine.backfeed.cc/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/nails-1024x683.jpg\" alt=\"nails\" width=\"460\" height=\"307\" />an nature is to effect change, to be recognized as a unique individual offering a special contribution to the world. Our failing struggle for personal agency is at the center of\r\nmodern life. Winnowed out through the funnel of education and specialization is a person\'s imagined goals—challenging work, suitable income, meaningful output, adequate leisure. We settle. Our lofty aspirations eventually dwindle to this: work is toilsome and necessarily serves someone else\'s interest. That\'s why we get paid. A key element in the mainstream economy\'s idealized self becomes not personal agency, but the capacity to surrender—enervation of judgment and erosion of the independent spirit.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">To perpetuate this ignorance, contemporary culture separates knowing from doing. The way we come to know a hammer is not by staring at it, but grabbing hold of it and using it. The way things come to exist for us is not as free-floating objects out of context, but as equipment for action, within some actual worldly situation. If thinking is bound up with action, then the task of getting an adequate grasp on the world, intellectually, depends on us doing stuff in it. On all sides we see fewer occasions for the exercise of judgment, although human excellence calls forth the necessity of such judgment.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">It is a tragic loss to our society that manual competence is an ideal that finds little accommodation today. Some argue that it is irresponsible to educate the young for the trades, which are somehow identified with jobs of the past. We have a generation of students who can answer questions on tests, but who can\'t do anything. </span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The use of tools answers to some permanent requirement of our nature. Many people discover with surprise the greater sense of agency and competence that comes from doing manual work compared to \"knowledge work.\" More surprising is that people find manual work more engaging intellectually. The physical circumstances of jobs performed by carpenters, plumbers, and auto mechanics vary too much for them to be executed by idiots.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">This labor makes one feel human, not like a cog in a machine. The trades draw those who live by their own powers, free not only of deadening abstraction, but also of the rising insecurities endemic to our current economic life. This work relieves us of the felt need to offer chattering interpretations of ourselves to vindicate our worth. We can simply point: the building stands, the car now runs, the garden is abundant. There is a cognitive richness of manual work; work that is useful proves to also be intellectually absorbing.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For many in mainstream society a good life is an amorphous goal. Living a meaningful life is seen as a foolish utopian dream. But it is not. Here at Twin Oaks our labor produces tangible outcomes that markedly improve our lives and the lives of those we live with. But more, our work brings us new skills, coherence to our lives, pleasure to our minds, and satisfaction to our souls.</span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Trades, Skill And Education - The Separation of Knowing From Doing','','inherit','closed','closed','','413-revision-v1','','','2016-02-17 14:36:04','2016-02-17 14:36:04','',413,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/413-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(430,8,'2016-02-17 14:36:25','2016-02-17 14:36:25','<blockquote>\r\nThe  author of this article lives in an income-sharing community in Virginia, Twin Oaks.  Twin Oaks is a communal group established in 1967 with 100 members.  Income is earned by businesses on the property. Everything is owned equally and no member gets any salary or wages.</blockquote>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">There is a profound disconnect between what is taught about any trade, and the knowledge actually needed to perform that trade well. Medical students learn all the bones of the body, but are not taught how to listen carefully to patients. MBA students are taught personnel theories and the intersection of supply and demand, but not, say, how to deal with a mentally ill employee—or boss. This is because the central purpose of education is not mastery of useful skills, but through non-relevant rigorous requirements, screening people out. </span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">What do business leaders say about this disconnect? It has become the bon-ton among corporate recruiters to claim no or little interest in student\'s grades. This might have some solid ground. In a famous </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">study</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> of air traffic controllers, a job requiring complex decision making, educational achievement made for worse air traffic controllers.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Not everyone ignores this. Twin</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> Oaks is a complex society that runs several profitable businesses in addition to building buildings, fixing cars, and raising food; there is a great need for a wide array of skills. There are almost no barriers to taking on a task or job of almost any complexity. What Twin Oaks offers is on-the-job training—minus the training. A profound benefit of living at Twin Oaks is being able to be drawn to a job and to do it immediately, not after four or seven years of education, plus some additional handful of years working your way up through the ranks.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><img class=\" wp-image-419 alignleft\" src=\"http://magazine.backfeed.cc/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/photo-1452980904795-dc36a4d90da4-1024x492.jpg\" alt=\"photo-1452980904795-dc36a4d90da4\" width=\"512\" height=\"246\" />\r\nWhat the community has discovered is that training and credentials don\'t matter. Sure, a skilled plumber can fix a leaking pipe better than a philosophy student, but in two months of fixing leaking pipes, the philosophy student </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">is</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> a skilled plumber. Every member learns new skills, takes on new jobs—there are no hurdles in the way, other tha\r\nn willingness and competence. Sometimes people try a job and realize after a while that they don\'t like it, so they stop. Most members want variety in their work lives so no one chooses to do forty hours of the same job. Most members eventually sculpt a work life that is challenging, fulfilling, and rewarding.\r\n</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">In the mainstream, individuals claim to pursue education as a path to a more fulfilling life. What common threads of a fulfilling life should education be concerned with providing? Perhaps these: satisfying work, intellectual challenge, being of use, adequate pay. That is the implicit deal that higher education offers: sacrifice your childhood and young adulthood to us and in return your education will open the doors to a better, more bountiful, more challenging future. That is a promise that is increasingly broken.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Teenagers, intent on finding a career, must first gather all the credentials for that career before getting a chance to even see if they are suited to that work, but once they go through the time and expense to get the credentials, they are pretty well stuck with that career, whether they like it or not. Consequently, millions of people are in jobs that are other than they anticipated—lesser, worse—with no easy option for going back to square one and getting re-credentialed for another, more engaging career. After all, </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">this</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> job was worse than expected, the next could prove just as disappointing. One of the fastest growing segments of the student body at community colleges is people who already have a four-year degree and return to get a marketable skill. </span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">College serves another purpose—a purpose colleges don\'t mention in their course catalog— colleges habituate young people to accept a mismatch between form and content, official representations and reality. The passing of examinations, meeting of course deadlines, and disciplined study for the sake of mastering a body of knowledge demonstrates a willingness to conform to organizational discipline and displays the disposition needed to develop competence in a bureaucracy. Intellectuals pursue an academic career to become professionalized and this professionalization leads people not to higher intellectual rigor, but to stop thinking. The corporate world deals in abstractions, true, but trafficking in abstractions is not the same as thinking.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">White-collar professions have been routinized and degraded: standardized tests remove a teacher\'s discretion in the curriculum; strict sentencing guidelines prevent a judge from judging. Efforts of managers are not toward some tangible outcome. </span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The desire of hum<img class=\"wp-image-416 alignright\" src=\"http://magazine.backfeed.cc/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/nails-1024x683.jpg\" alt=\"nails\" width=\"460\" height=\"307\" />an nature is to effect change, to be recognized as a unique individual offering a special contribution to the world. Our failing struggle for personal agency is at the center of\r\nmodern life. Winnowed out through the funnel of education and specialization is a person\'s imagined goals—challenging work, suitable income, meaningful output, adequate leisure. We settle. Our lofty aspirations eventually dwindle to this: work is toilsome and necessarily serves someone else\'s interest. That\'s why we get paid. A key element in the mainstream economy\'s idealized self becomes not personal agency, but the capacity to surrender—enervation of judgment and erosion of the independent spirit.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">To perpetuate this ignorance, contemporary culture separates knowing from doing. The way we come to know a hammer is not by staring at it, but grabbing hold of it and using it. The way things come to exist for us is not as free-floating objects out of context, but as equipment for action, within some actual worldly situation. If thinking is bound up with action, then the task of getting an adequate grasp on the world, intellectually, depends on us doing stuff in it. On all sides we see fewer occasions for the exercise of judgment, although human excellence calls forth the necessity of such judgment.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">It is a tragic loss to our society that manual competence is an ideal that finds little accommodation today. Some argue that it is irresponsible to educate the young for the trades, which are somehow identified with jobs of the past. We have a generation of students who can answer questions on tests, but who can\'t do anything. </span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The use of tools answers to some permanent requirement of our nature. Many people discover with surprise the greater sense of agency and competence that comes from doing manual work compared to \"knowledge work.\" More surprising is that people find manual work more engaging intellectually. The physical circumstances of jobs performed by carpenters, plumbers, and auto mechanics vary too much for them to be executed by idiots.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">This labor makes one feel human, not like a cog in a machine. The trades draw those who live by their own powers, free not only of deadening abstraction, but also of the rising insecurities endemic to our current economic life. This work relieves us of the felt need to offer chattering interpretations of ourselves to vindicate our worth. We can simply point: the building stands, the car now runs, the garden is abundant. There is a cognitive richness of manual work; work that is useful proves to also be intellectually absorbing.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For many in mainstream society a good life is an amorphous goal. Living a meaningful life is seen as a foolish utopian dream. But it is not. Here at Twin Oaks our labor produces tangible outcomes that markedly improve our lives and the lives of those we live with. But more, our work brings us new skills, coherence to our lives, pleasure to our minds, and satisfaction to our souls.</span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Trades, Skill And Education - The Separation of Knowing From Doing','','inherit','closed','closed','','413-revision-v1','','','2016-02-17 14:36:25','2016-02-17 14:36:25','',413,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/413-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(431,8,'2016-02-18 09:40:12','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<p id=\"ca06\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--h3\">This paper will explore how businesses could create commercial opportunities in addressing the needs of the developed and developing world through <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Block_chain_%28database%29\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Block_chain_%28database%29\">Blockchain </a>enabled <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peer-to-peer_lending\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peer-to-peer_lending\">P2P financial services</a>, and how progressive governments can create <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"https://idcubed.org/digital-law/the-rise-of-digital-common-law/\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"https://idcubed.org/digital-law/the-rise-of-digital-common-law/\">modern and efficient civil infrastructure</a>, based on blockchain technology, that will help to facilitate greater transparency, security, and scale, to enable a more competitive and just nation.</p>\r\n<p id=\"f86f\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">I seek to illustrate the value of identity, as a fundamental human property, and its inherent and intrinsic value. As well as how a blockchain enabled identification system is the fundamental key to unlocking the commercial and social power of <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"https://idcubed.org/digital-law/socialstack/\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"https://idcubed.org/digital-law/socialstack/\">“the new economy”</a> that can enhance innovation in the financial services industry, the emerging <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"http://www.ibm.com/common/ssi/cgi-bin/ssialias?infotype=PM&amp;subtype=XB&amp;htmlfid=GBE03620USEN\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"http://www.ibm.com/common/ssi/cgi-bin/ssialias?infotype=PM&amp;subtype=XB&amp;htmlfid=GBE03620USEN\">“internet of things”</a>, while at the same time providing a reclaimed notion of privacy and security to the individual, and a fertile environment for innovation, commerce, and trade.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3 id=\"c0f8\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">The Facebook Effect</h3>\r\n<p id=\"5d3e\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">When <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"http://zerotoonebook.com/\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"http://zerotoonebook.com/\">Peter Thiel</a> was considering investing $500,000 USD in the startup company facebook in 2004 he asked Mark Zuckerberg;</p>\r\n<p id=\"5d52\" class=\"graf--p graf--startsWithDoubleQuote graf-after--p\"><strong>“What makes Facebook 10x better and not just an incremental change over MySpace, Friendster, Geocities, Bebo, etc?</strong></p>\r\n<p id=\"4235\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">To which Zuckerberg responded;</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p id=\"f759\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">“Facebook is the first social network that makes you confirm your identity. It turns out identity is important,”</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p id=\"b960\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">At the time, Facebook provided the best probable Identity solution for people’s desire to connect and communicate on the internet. Creating a <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"http://platformed.info/\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"http://platformed.info/\">platform</a> where its intrinsic value was not the ability to connect with your friends, family and wider community, but a centralized depository of real identities and an ecosystem of trust on the internet.</p>\r\n<p id=\"d85e\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">It’s not about fake identities or alternate identities, or networking in the abstract. It’s about people representing themselves accurately on the internet, as much of the early attempts at social networking had been about creating alternate worlds; virtual realities in which maybe one pretends to be a dog, and another pretends to be a cat, and they sort of interact in some strange new way in a different medium.</p>\r\n<p id=\"88da\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Facebook, in essence, was one of the first companies to mirror the real identities of the real world onto the internet, which gives it both its power, and raises some of the concerns people have about privacy and information.</p>\r\n<p id=\"1ee5\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Currently we live in a world where States issue identity and proof of existence, and rightfully so, attest to the validity of said existence, coupled with the trust and the authority of the institutions that hold our society together. State services like taxation, criminal justice and voting revolve around the idea of a person being clearly identified. This trust in the State and the surrounding institutions is what provides the framework for businesses to thrive and for trade to be facilitated in a way that property can be acquired and wealth can be created. Moreover, the very notion of the State is partially defined by a registered ledger of persons who are members of that State.</p>\r\n<p id=\"e9a5\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Therefore Identity as property has an inherent and intangible value. <em class=\"markup--em markup--p-em\">However; who should own that identity, what is its value, who should control it, and how can that value be realized for the owner?</em></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 id=\"d06e\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Identity, the Core Building Block</h3>\r\n<p id=\"5b9b\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Our society has abdicated the most fundamental core human property, identity, over to technologically enabled advertising businesses, under the guise of “providing you with better service”. We freely give our property away, in the form of registering our interests, likes, searches, and check-ins so that these “service providers” can on-aggregate; repurpose, resell, and remit advertisements of things we may, or may not want at any (touch)point of our existence. They don’t get remunerated for their accuracy as much as they do for our attention, so can it ultimately be considered a good service? These companies over the last 20 years have amassed historical profits, and rightfully so, for monopolizing a shrewdly acquired valuable property such as identity on mass. In relation to extending the notion of identity and the opportunities that States are not able to provide in the <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"https://idcubed.org/digital-law/the-rise-of-digital-common-law/\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"https://idcubed.org/digital-law/the-rise-of-digital-common-law/\">transnational environment of the internet</a>; Identity services such as single sign on (SSO) services on the internet eg. sign in with Google, Facebook, Twitter etc., have provided these companies with breakout opportunities to lock in network effects and to expand their ability to “serve you better”.</p>\r\n<p id=\"c599\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Unfortunately, due to the centralized nature of these firms; specific attributes of our stored identity have become vulnerable to attack. As a centralized repository of these valuable assets, they ultimately become prime targets as they hold massive amounts of information and a path of least resistance for hackers, i.e. they only have to go to one place to steal a lot of stuff. Enterprises currently take the unnecessary risk of <em class=\"markup--em markup--p-em\">information spillage </em>by using processes that inherently have single points of failure, and multiple hops where such a failure can occur. This single point of failure has a massive impact on the security of our information. This is a fundamental area where blockchain technology in it’s now, varied forms, can make a difference to how data is stored and retrieved.</p>\r\n<p id=\"734e\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">A <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/eb1f8256-7b4b-11e5-a1fe-567b37f80b64.html\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/eb1f8256-7b4b-11e5-a1fe-567b37f80b64.html\">blockchain</a> is a public ledger that records and validates every single transaction made in a system. What makes this network so unique and secured is that all transactions are authorized and backed by thousands of computers (called miners), achieving consensus on each transaction. It is fully decentralized, so no one owns it, thereby there’s no single point of attack. Despite its openness, the Blockchain is highly tamper resistant. Attempting to manipulate the state of the ledger requires harnessing enough computational resources to overwhelm the rest of the network. Changing a historical block becomes exponentially harder the deeper it is in the chain. The economic incentive set forward by the block reward creates a feedback loop that tends to increase security by encouraging users to spend more computational power into the competition to find new blocks.</p>\r\n<p id=\"95a0\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">This decentralized security model, based on trustless consensus and full data redundancy, removes the single point of failure common to traditional centralized databases and makes the Blockchain robust even <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antifragile\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antifragile\">“Anti-fragile”</a> in many regards.</p>\r\n<p id=\"ccff\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Using the blockchain to secure and attest identity, is a means to thwart these efforts, but at the same time provide the ability to create new opportunities for business innovation, as well, as providing a mechanism for developing nations to gain greater access the global economy.</p>\r\n<p id=\"521b\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">There is no question that there are many people on earth that have little, to no verifiable identity; these individuals of emerging economies are mired in the reality of inequality somewhat on the account that they don’t have credible verification to their own, inalienable property; Identity. Without this form of property right, they have little ability, if any, to utilize whatever sub-standard means they have to pull themselves from poverty at a rate that would be acceptable or inline with members of the developed world. Cost and inefficient infrastructure make common things to you or I, in the developed world; like opening a bank account and obtaining credit facilities, impossible.</p>\r\n<p id=\"2979\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Enabling developing nations to <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Disruptive_innovation\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Disruptive_innovation\">“leapfrog”</a> the legacy systems of the developed world, and in many ways inducing the <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Backporting\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Backporting\">“backporting” </a>of these technologies to the underbanked in the developed world through blockchain technologies and complementary <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"http://stackshare.io/stacks/emerging-technology\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"http://stackshare.io/stacks/emerging-technology\">“emerging technology stacks”</a> can provide the portability and security of identity and information, in ways that are vastly more efficient and beneficial to the constructs that we currently have. Users will be able to own their own identity, have it irrefutably registered on the blockchain where only they can access it, and or provide details that are necessary to third parties when they see fit in a secure and private manner.</p>\r\n<p id=\"ab36\" class=\"graf--p graf--startsWithDoubleQuote graf-after--p\"><a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"https://idcubed.org/chapter-2-self-sovereignty-matters/\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"https://idcubed.org/chapter-2-self-sovereignty-matters/\">“Self-Sovereign Identity”</a>, a concept where the individual has ultimate control over their identity and is the final arbiter of who can access and use their data and personal information, is an emerging concept in digital identity that has primarily hinged on “identity providers” (States) and Identity “Arbiters” (Advertising Technology Platform companies), which are the entities that issue, attest, and hold considerable control over the value of our identity. Self-sovereign identity is a reclamation of property so that the the individual is securely in control of their identity and can use it in ways that serves their interests and well being.</p>\r\n<p id=\"5939\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Moreover, with <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"https://idcubed.org/chapter-2-self-sovereignty-matters/\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"https://idcubed.org/chapter-2-self-sovereignty-matters/\">self-sovereign identity</a> coupled with new advancements in<a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multi-factor_authentication\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multi-factor_authentication\">“Multi-factor/Multi-signatory technology</a>” identification platforms”, the individual still has the option of letting a trusted “social notary”, ie friend or identity verification provider, manage their identity in “Trust” as a failsafe to any anomalies or <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Black_Swan_%28Taleb_book%29\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Black_Swan_%28Taleb_book%29\">“Black Swan”</a> events.</p>\r\n<p id=\"6267\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Individuals of developed nations, in the coming age of the internet of things, will seek “secure by design” <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"http://www.ibm.com/common/ssi/cgi-bin/ssialias?infotype=PM&amp;subtype=XB&amp;htmlfid=GBE03620USEN\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"http://www.ibm.com/common/ssi/cgi-bin/ssialias?infotype=PM&amp;subtype=XB&amp;htmlfid=GBE03620USEN\">“device democracy”</a>, where information belongs securely to the user and which can only be obtained through identity and information management systems that are user friendly, secure, in-corruptible, and attested, because there are few consumers today that would condone of a single organization housing all their information about what they search, who they call, what they email, or where they\'re heading with their automated self driving car.</p>\r\n<p id=\"5100\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">In the developing world, Self-Sovereign identity on the blockchain can provide legitimacy to displaced people and refugees. Digital identities registered and controlled through a blockchain require no central company or organization to maintain, and can survive political and social turmoil so that refugees can retain access to their digital identities and property even under such difficult conditions. eg. what does it mean for the Taliban to say you’re a criminal, and that you don’t own the land you live on if you’re displaced from the home that your family has lived on for 3 generations in Afghanistan?</p>\r\n\r\n<h3 id=\"158f\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Design, or Complex Coordination</h3>\r\n<p id=\"f7a3\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">There are very few breakout, <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"http://www.exponentialorgs.com/\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"http://www.exponentialorgs.com/\">transformational innovations</a> in our world today, but unequivocally, the Blockchain is one that deserves the title. However, where I believe that the technology is underrated is in the area of creativity in its application. Whether this is due to its nascency or resistance, I’m not sure, but I think that the Blockchain space has many great components that innovators and incumbents can use to coordinate complex, and sometimes disparate technologies that synthesize into some highly differentiated and competitive products that <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"http://www.exponentialorgs.com/\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"http://www.exponentialorgs.com/\">have the potential to be an order, or multiple orders of magnitude</a> greater than what our world currently has.</p>\r\n<p id=\"5e4e\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">The ability to re-imagine how civil services are delivered, consumed, and ultimately exploited is possible today because of the emergence of several technologies: Blockchain technology like <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"https://www.ethereum.org/\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"https://www.ethereum.org/\">“Ethereum”</a> eliminates single points of failure by facilitating direct exchange between parties within a fully auditable cryptographically secured system facilitated by <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"http://www.fastcolabs.com/3035723/app-economy/smart-contracts-could-be-cryptocurrencys-killer-app\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"http://www.fastcolabs.com/3035723/app-economy/smart-contracts-could-be-cryptocurrencys-killer-app\">“smart contracts</a>”. Distributed consensus ledgers facilitate transactions on a large scale without settlement or counterparty risk since the transaction settles in gross in real time and assets exchange hands as described by the transaction details. Disputes can be resolved quickly by referencing the blockchain. The efficiency of a distributed digital ledger broadens when transmitting assets between accounts or people. A proper identity system architecture ensures a secure environment when interacting with the blockchain.</p>\r\n<p id=\"b82c\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Distributed data storage systems like <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"https://ipfs.io/\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"https://ipfs.io/\">“Inter Planetary File System”</a> (IPFS) which is a peer-to-peer distributed file system capable of sharing the same files with millions of nodes, has a completely decentralized architecture, secure and efficient peer-to-peer block distribution, and a path-based naming system supporting distinguishing mutable and immutable names. IPFS is capable of evolving the web to take advantage of versioning, p2p distribution, cryptographic operations, and decentralized publishing.</p>\r\n<p id=\"ec0f\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Emerging encryption technologies in combination with multi-factor/multi-signatory authentication security allow for combining privacy with the public nature of the blockchain. This is especially critical for digital identity based on<a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"http://www.pwc.com/gx/en/industries/financial-services/publications/anti-money-laundering-know-your-customer-quick-reference-guide.html\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"http://www.pwc.com/gx/en/industries/financial-services/publications/anti-money-laundering-know-your-customer-quick-reference-guide.html\">AML/KYC</a> (Anti-Money Laundering/Know Your Customer)</p>\r\n<p id=\"c2be\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Our current one-dimensional authentication systems are no longer effective. Synchronized token systems with multi-factor authentication are one recommended security method for effective controls. However, these tokens only facilitate access control and can’t be used to sign and broadcast cryptographic transactions on distributed ledgers. Many technologies now have the ability to support multiple factors of authentication for securing financial assets or access control transactions:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol class=\"postList\">\r\n	<li id=\"34c3\" class=\"graf--li graf-after--p\">Who you are — Biometric verification</li>\r\n	<li id=\"6adc\" class=\"graf--li graf-after--li\">What you have — The key embedded on the device</li>\r\n	<li id=\"73bb\" class=\"graf--li graf-after--li\">What you know — Verification of pin or other security information</li>\r\n	<li id=\"e790\" class=\"graf--li graf-after--li\">Where you are — Geo-fencing based on device location</li>\r\n	<li id=\"a219\" class=\"graf--li graf-after--li\">Who knows you — Social networks</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p id=\"5519\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--li\">Requiring multiple authentication methods to sign transactions strengthens security measures by applying additional layers of security. Cryptographic security functions that requires M-of-N keys to sign transactions. M represents the number of keys needed to verify a transaction and N designates the total number of authorized keys. 2-of-3 is the most common security measure for multi-signature blockchain functions and is more secure than a single private key. Requiring multiple keys that are each secured by a different authentication factor increases security by eliminating single points of failure for any one authorized individual. Requiring multiple individuals to sign a transaction in this way creates secure channels for the the digital transfer of financial assets on a trusted distributed ledger</p>\r\n<p id=\"12b2\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Even more radical new approaches to innovation with decentralized/distributed technology on the blockchain is The <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"http://enigma.media.mit.edu/enigma_full.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"http://enigma.media.mit.edu/enigma_full.pdf\">“MIT Enigma Machine”</a> a decentralized cloud platform with guaranteed privacy. Private data is stored, shared and analyzed without ever being fully revealed to any party. Secure multi-party computation all enabled by the blockchain, and a project inspired by Ethereum: <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"https://eprint.iacr.org/2015/675.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"https://eprint.iacr.org/2015/675.pdf\">“Hawk”</a>, a <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zero-knowledge_proof\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zero-knowledge_proof\">“zero knowledge protocol”</a> which allows a statement or transaction to be verified without conveying any information about it apart from the fact it’s true or adds up, thus retaining transactional privacy from the public’s view.</p>\r\n<p id=\"eeda\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">An implementation of technologies coordinated in an integrated fashion as described above, would open a variety of dimensions for innovation across financial, legal and civil services. <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"http://www.google.com/patents/US5086469\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"http://www.google.com/patents/US5086469\">“Selective Disclosure” </a>features, where the user can encrypt the attributes associated to their identity and selectively choose what information they wish to share; essentially our most sensitive data, could securely store; genomics, biometrics, financial data, keys, codes etc. Which could be linked to the identities in privacy-preserving ways which could prove to be crucial enablers, service enhancements, and competitive advantages for governments, banks, insurance providers, and public health institutions where the data attributes can be very personal and sensitive.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3 id=\"7b3b\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Intrepid Ventures invests, builds, and accelerates Blockchain and IoT companies solving the world’s most difficult problems.</h3>\r\n<p id=\"5014\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\"><em class=\"markup--em markup--p-em\">If you are interested in learning more about the rest of this whitepaper, our active projects in this space, how we can help your company design competitive new businesses with for your organization, or you’re an entrepreneur or technology leader looking for an interesting project to work for; please feel free to contact me here on </em><a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"https://hk.linkedin.com/in/collinthompson\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"https://hk.linkedin.com/in/collinthompson\"><em class=\"markup--em markup--p-em\">linkedin</em></a><em class=\"markup--em markup--p-em\"> or by email at </em><a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"https://medium.com/@collin_thompson/fintech-2-0-e17491431103\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"\"><em class=\"markup--em markup--p-em\">collin@intrepid.ventures.com</em></a></p>\r\n<p id=\"039a\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">The second half of this white paper explores solutions and uses cases that cover</p>\r\n<p id=\"1690\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\"><strong class=\"markup--strong markup--p-strong\">Blockchain identity, biometrics, and Multi-Factor identification across;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul class=\"postList\">\r\n	<li id=\"2a85\" class=\"graf--li graf-after--p\"><a class=\"markup--anchor markup--li-anchor\" href=\"http://www.ibm.com/mobilefirst/us/en/bring-your-own-device/byod.html\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"http://www.ibm.com/mobilefirst/us/en/bring-your-own-device/byod.html\">BYOD (Bring your own device)</a></li>\r\n	<li id=\"af45\" class=\"graf--li graf-after--li\">Payments (blockchain rails for transnational payments)</li>\r\n	<li id=\"13fe\" class=\"graf--li graf-after--li\"><a class=\"markup--anchor markup--li-anchor\" href=\"https://news.bitcoin.com/holy-trinity-blockchain-medical-records-wearable-tech/\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"https://news.bitcoin.com/holy-trinity-blockchain-medical-records-wearable-tech/\">Blockchain, Electronic Medical Records and Wearable Tech</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p id=\"03ad\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--li\"><strong class=\"markup--strong markup--p-strong\">How governments can improve legacy systems and provide better infrastructure for competitiveness and quality of life.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul class=\"postList\">\r\n	<li id=\"9eb4\" class=\"graf--li graf-after--p\"><a class=\"markup--anchor markup--li-anchor\" href=\"http://rossdawsonblog.com/weblog/archives/2014/09/new-layer-economy-enabled-m2m-payments-internet-things.html\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"http://rossdawsonblog.com/weblog/archives/2014/09/new-layer-economy-enabled-m2m-payments-internet-things.html\">Machine-to-machine payments</a> and smart merchants for the Internet of things</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p id=\"f714\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--li\"><strong class=\"markup--strong markup--p-strong\">How can banks provide modern peer-to-peer financial services that provide them with sustainability into the new economy.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul class=\"postList\">\r\n	<li id=\"0cda\" class=\"graf--li graf-after--p\"><a class=\"markup--anchor markup--li-anchor\" href=\"https://securityintelligence.com/how-banks-are-leveraging-bitcoin-and-blockchain-technologies/\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"https://securityintelligence.com/how-banks-are-leveraging-bitcoin-and-blockchain-technologies/\">Bank attested Identity services</a></li>\r\n	<li id=\"146a\" class=\"graf--li graf-after--li\">Credit scoring and reputation</li>\r\n	<li id=\"dba9\" class=\"graf--li graf-after--li\">Insurance</li>\r\n	<li id=\"0eca\" class=\"graf--li graf-after--li\">Payments/remittances; wallets, NFC, and reputation</li>\r\n	<li id=\"8c2d\" class=\"graf--li graf-after--li\">Credit (Mortgages/Car loans)</li>\r\n	<li id=\"6171\" class=\"graf--li graf-after--li graf--last\">Consumer credit (shopping/credit cards)</li>\r\n</ul>','FinTech 2.0: Identities, Blockchains And The Prospect For A Better Global Society','','draft','closed','open','','fintech-2-0-identities-blockchains-and-the-prospect-for-a-better-global-society','','','2016-02-18 09:40:12','2016-02-18 09:40:12','',0,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/?p=431',0,'post','',0),(432,8,'2016-02-18 09:40:12','2016-02-18 09:40:12','<p id=\"ca06\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--h3\">This paper will explore how businesses could create commercial opportunities in addressing the needs of the developed and developing world through <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Block_chain_%28database%29\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Block_chain_%28database%29\">Blockchain </a>enabled <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peer-to-peer_lending\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peer-to-peer_lending\">P2P financial services</a>, and how progressive governments can create <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"https://idcubed.org/digital-law/the-rise-of-digital-common-law/\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"https://idcubed.org/digital-law/the-rise-of-digital-common-law/\">modern and efficient civil infrastructure</a>, based on blockchain technology, that will help to facilitate greater transparency, security, and scale, to enable a more competitive and just nation.</p>\r\n<p id=\"f86f\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">I seek to illustrate the value of identity, as a fundamental human property, and its inherent and intrinsic value. As well as how a blockchain enabled identification system is the fundamental key to unlocking the commercial and social power of <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"https://idcubed.org/digital-law/socialstack/\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"https://idcubed.org/digital-law/socialstack/\">“the new economy”</a> that can enhance innovation in the financial services industry, the emerging <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"http://www.ibm.com/common/ssi/cgi-bin/ssialias?infotype=PM&amp;subtype=XB&amp;htmlfid=GBE03620USEN\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"http://www.ibm.com/common/ssi/cgi-bin/ssialias?infotype=PM&amp;subtype=XB&amp;htmlfid=GBE03620USEN\">“internet of things”</a>, while at the same time providing a reclaimed notion of privacy and security to the individual, and a fertile environment for innovation, commerce, and trade.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3 id=\"c0f8\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">The Facebook Effect</h3>\r\n<p id=\"5d3e\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">When <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"http://zerotoonebook.com/\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"http://zerotoonebook.com/\">Peter Thiel</a> was considering investing $500,000 USD in the startup company facebook in 2004 he asked Mark Zuckerberg;</p>\r\n<p id=\"5d52\" class=\"graf--p graf--startsWithDoubleQuote graf-after--p\"><strong>“What makes Facebook 10x better and not just an incremental change over MySpace, Friendster, Geocities, Bebo, etc?</strong></p>\r\n<p id=\"4235\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">To which Zuckerberg responded;</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p id=\"f759\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">“Facebook is the first social network that makes you confirm your identity. It turns out identity is important,”</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p id=\"b960\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">At the time, Facebook provided the best probable Identity solution for people’s desire to connect and communicate on the internet. Creating a <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"http://platformed.info/\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"http://platformed.info/\">platform</a> where its intrinsic value was not the ability to connect with your friends, family and wider community, but a centralized depository of real identities and an ecosystem of trust on the internet.</p>\r\n<p id=\"d85e\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">It’s not about fake identities or alternate identities, or networking in the abstract. It’s about people representing themselves accurately on the internet, as much of the early attempts at social networking had been about creating alternate worlds; virtual realities in which maybe one pretends to be a dog, and another pretends to be a cat, and they sort of interact in some strange new way in a different medium.</p>\r\n<p id=\"88da\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Facebook, in essence, was one of the first companies to mirror the real identities of the real world onto the internet, which gives it both its power, and raises some of the concerns people have about privacy and information.</p>\r\n<p id=\"1ee5\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Currently we live in a world where States issue identity and proof of existence, and rightfully so, attest to the validity of said existence, coupled with the trust and the authority of the institutions that hold our society together. State services like taxation, criminal justice and voting revolve around the idea of a person being clearly identified. This trust in the State and the surrounding institutions is what provides the framework for businesses to thrive and for trade to be facilitated in a way that property can be acquired and wealth can be created. Moreover, the very notion of the State is partially defined by a registered ledger of persons who are members of that State.</p>\r\n<p id=\"e9a5\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Therefore Identity as property has an inherent and intangible value. <em class=\"markup--em markup--p-em\">However; who should own that identity, what is its value, who should control it, and how can that value be realized for the owner?</em></p>\r\n\r\n<h3 id=\"d06e\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Identity, the Core Building Block</h3>\r\n<p id=\"5b9b\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Our society has abdicated the most fundamental core human property, identity, over to technologically enabled advertising businesses, under the guise of “providing you with better service”. We freely give our property away, in the form of registering our interests, likes, searches, and check-ins so that these “service providers” can on-aggregate; repurpose, resell, and remit advertisements of things we may, or may not want at any (touch)point of our existence. They don’t get remunerated for their accuracy as much as they do for our attention, so can it ultimately be considered a good service? These companies over the last 20 years have amassed historical profits, and rightfully so, for monopolizing a shrewdly acquired valuable property such as identity on mass. In relation to extending the notion of identity and the opportunities that States are not able to provide in the <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"https://idcubed.org/digital-law/the-rise-of-digital-common-law/\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"https://idcubed.org/digital-law/the-rise-of-digital-common-law/\">transnational environment of the internet</a>; Identity services such as single sign on (SSO) services on the internet eg. sign in with Google, Facebook, Twitter etc., have provided these companies with breakout opportunities to lock in network effects and to expand their ability to “serve you better”.</p>\r\n<p id=\"c599\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Unfortunately, due to the centralized nature of these firms; specific attributes of our stored identity have become vulnerable to attack. As a centralized repository of these valuable assets, they ultimately become prime targets as they hold massive amounts of information and a path of least resistance for hackers, i.e. they only have to go to one place to steal a lot of stuff. Enterprises currently take the unnecessary risk of <em class=\"markup--em markup--p-em\">information spillage </em>by using processes that inherently have single points of failure, and multiple hops where such a failure can occur. This single point of failure has a massive impact on the security of our information. This is a fundamental area where blockchain technology in it’s now, varied forms, can make a difference to how data is stored and retrieved.</p>\r\n<p id=\"734e\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">A <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/eb1f8256-7b4b-11e5-a1fe-567b37f80b64.html\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/eb1f8256-7b4b-11e5-a1fe-567b37f80b64.html\">blockchain</a> is a public ledger that records and validates every single transaction made in a system. What makes this network so unique and secured is that all transactions are authorized and backed by thousands of computers (called miners), achieving consensus on each transaction. It is fully decentralized, so no one owns it, thereby there’s no single point of attack. Despite its openness, the Blockchain is highly tamper resistant. Attempting to manipulate the state of the ledger requires harnessing enough computational resources to overwhelm the rest of the network. Changing a historical block becomes exponentially harder the deeper it is in the chain. The economic incentive set forward by the block reward creates a feedback loop that tends to increase security by encouraging users to spend more computational power into the competition to find new blocks.</p>\r\n<p id=\"95a0\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">This decentralized security model, based on trustless consensus and full data redundancy, removes the single point of failure common to traditional centralized databases and makes the Blockchain robust even <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antifragile\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antifragile\">“Anti-fragile”</a> in many regards.</p>\r\n<p id=\"ccff\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Using the blockchain to secure and attest identity, is a means to thwart these efforts, but at the same time provide the ability to create new opportunities for business innovation, as well, as providing a mechanism for developing nations to gain greater access the global economy.</p>\r\n<p id=\"521b\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">There is no question that there are many people on earth that have little, to no verifiable identity; these individuals of emerging economies are mired in the reality of inequality somewhat on the account that they don’t have credible verification to their own, inalienable property; Identity. Without this form of property right, they have little ability, if any, to utilize whatever sub-standard means they have to pull themselves from poverty at a rate that would be acceptable or inline with members of the developed world. Cost and inefficient infrastructure make common things to you or I, in the developed world; like opening a bank account and obtaining credit facilities, impossible.</p>\r\n<p id=\"2979\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Enabling developing nations to <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Disruptive_innovation\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Disruptive_innovation\">“leapfrog”</a> the legacy systems of the developed world, and in many ways inducing the <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Backporting\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Backporting\">“backporting” </a>of these technologies to the underbanked in the developed world through blockchain technologies and complementary <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"http://stackshare.io/stacks/emerging-technology\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"http://stackshare.io/stacks/emerging-technology\">“emerging technology stacks”</a> can provide the portability and security of identity and information, in ways that are vastly more efficient and beneficial to the constructs that we currently have. Users will be able to own their own identity, have it irrefutably registered on the blockchain where only they can access it, and or provide details that are necessary to third parties when they see fit in a secure and private manner.</p>\r\n<p id=\"ab36\" class=\"graf--p graf--startsWithDoubleQuote graf-after--p\"><a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"https://idcubed.org/chapter-2-self-sovereignty-matters/\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"https://idcubed.org/chapter-2-self-sovereignty-matters/\">“Self-Sovereign Identity”</a>, a concept where the individual has ultimate control over their identity and is the final arbiter of who can access and use their data and personal information, is an emerging concept in digital identity that has primarily hinged on “identity providers” (States) and Identity “Arbiters” (Advertising Technology Platform companies), which are the entities that issue, attest, and hold considerable control over the value of our identity. Self-sovereign identity is a reclamation of property so that the the individual is securely in control of their identity and can use it in ways that serves their interests and well being.</p>\r\n<p id=\"5939\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Moreover, with <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"https://idcubed.org/chapter-2-self-sovereignty-matters/\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"https://idcubed.org/chapter-2-self-sovereignty-matters/\">self-sovereign identity</a> coupled with new advancements in<a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multi-factor_authentication\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multi-factor_authentication\">“Multi-factor/Multi-signatory technology</a>” identification platforms”, the individual still has the option of letting a trusted “social notary”, ie friend or identity verification provider, manage their identity in “Trust” as a failsafe to any anomalies or <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Black_Swan_%28Taleb_book%29\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Black_Swan_%28Taleb_book%29\">“Black Swan”</a> events.</p>\r\n<p id=\"6267\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Individuals of developed nations, in the coming age of the internet of things, will seek “secure by design” <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"http://www.ibm.com/common/ssi/cgi-bin/ssialias?infotype=PM&amp;subtype=XB&amp;htmlfid=GBE03620USEN\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"http://www.ibm.com/common/ssi/cgi-bin/ssialias?infotype=PM&amp;subtype=XB&amp;htmlfid=GBE03620USEN\">“device democracy”</a>, where information belongs securely to the user and which can only be obtained through identity and information management systems that are user friendly, secure, in-corruptible, and attested, because there are few consumers today that would condone of a single organization housing all their information about what they search, who they call, what they email, or where they\'re heading with their automated self driving car.</p>\r\n<p id=\"5100\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">In the developing world, Self-Sovereign identity on the blockchain can provide legitimacy to displaced people and refugees. Digital identities registered and controlled through a blockchain require no central company or organization to maintain, and can survive political and social turmoil so that refugees can retain access to their digital identities and property even under such difficult conditions. eg. what does it mean for the Taliban to say you’re a criminal, and that you don’t own the land you live on if you’re displaced from the home that your family has lived on for 3 generations in Afghanistan?</p>\r\n\r\n<h3 id=\"158f\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Design, or Complex Coordination</h3>\r\n<p id=\"f7a3\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">There are very few breakout, <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"http://www.exponentialorgs.com/\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"http://www.exponentialorgs.com/\">transformational innovations</a> in our world today, but unequivocally, the Blockchain is one that deserves the title. However, where I believe that the technology is underrated is in the area of creativity in its application. Whether this is due to its nascency or resistance, I’m not sure, but I think that the Blockchain space has many great components that innovators and incumbents can use to coordinate complex, and sometimes disparate technologies that synthesize into some highly differentiated and competitive products that <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"http://www.exponentialorgs.com/\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"http://www.exponentialorgs.com/\">have the potential to be an order, or multiple orders of magnitude</a> greater than what our world currently has.</p>\r\n<p id=\"5e4e\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">The ability to re-imagine how civil services are delivered, consumed, and ultimately exploited is possible today because of the emergence of several technologies: Blockchain technology like <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"https://www.ethereum.org/\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"https://www.ethereum.org/\">“Ethereum”</a> eliminates single points of failure by facilitating direct exchange between parties within a fully auditable cryptographically secured system facilitated by <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"http://www.fastcolabs.com/3035723/app-economy/smart-contracts-could-be-cryptocurrencys-killer-app\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"http://www.fastcolabs.com/3035723/app-economy/smart-contracts-could-be-cryptocurrencys-killer-app\">“smart contracts</a>”. Distributed consensus ledgers facilitate transactions on a large scale without settlement or counterparty risk since the transaction settles in gross in real time and assets exchange hands as described by the transaction details. Disputes can be resolved quickly by referencing the blockchain. The efficiency of a distributed digital ledger broadens when transmitting assets between accounts or people. A proper identity system architecture ensures a secure environment when interacting with the blockchain.</p>\r\n<p id=\"b82c\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Distributed data storage systems like <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"https://ipfs.io/\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"https://ipfs.io/\">“Inter Planetary File System”</a> (IPFS) which is a peer-to-peer distributed file system capable of sharing the same files with millions of nodes, has a completely decentralized architecture, secure and efficient peer-to-peer block distribution, and a path-based naming system supporting distinguishing mutable and immutable names. IPFS is capable of evolving the web to take advantage of versioning, p2p distribution, cryptographic operations, and decentralized publishing.</p>\r\n<p id=\"ec0f\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Emerging encryption technologies in combination with multi-factor/multi-signatory authentication security allow for combining privacy with the public nature of the blockchain. This is especially critical for digital identity based on<a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"http://www.pwc.com/gx/en/industries/financial-services/publications/anti-money-laundering-know-your-customer-quick-reference-guide.html\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"http://www.pwc.com/gx/en/industries/financial-services/publications/anti-money-laundering-know-your-customer-quick-reference-guide.html\">AML/KYC</a> (Anti-Money Laundering/Know Your Customer)</p>\r\n<p id=\"c2be\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Our current one-dimensional authentication systems are no longer effective. Synchronized token systems with multi-factor authentication are one recommended security method for effective controls. However, these tokens only facilitate access control and can’t be used to sign and broadcast cryptographic transactions on distributed ledgers. Many technologies now have the ability to support multiple factors of authentication for securing financial assets or access control transactions:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol class=\"postList\">\r\n	<li id=\"34c3\" class=\"graf--li graf-after--p\">Who you are — Biometric verification</li>\r\n	<li id=\"6adc\" class=\"graf--li graf-after--li\">What you have — The key embedded on the device</li>\r\n	<li id=\"73bb\" class=\"graf--li graf-after--li\">What you know — Verification of pin or other security information</li>\r\n	<li id=\"e790\" class=\"graf--li graf-after--li\">Where you are — Geo-fencing based on device location</li>\r\n	<li id=\"a219\" class=\"graf--li graf-after--li\">Who knows you — Social networks</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p id=\"5519\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--li\">Requiring multiple authentication methods to sign transactions strengthens security measures by applying additional layers of security. Cryptographic security functions that requires M-of-N keys to sign transactions. M represents the number of keys needed to verify a transaction and N designates the total number of authorized keys. 2-of-3 is the most common security measure for multi-signature blockchain functions and is more secure than a single private key. Requiring multiple keys that are each secured by a different authentication factor increases security by eliminating single points of failure for any one authorized individual. Requiring multiple individuals to sign a transaction in this way creates secure channels for the the digital transfer of financial assets on a trusted distributed ledger</p>\r\n<p id=\"12b2\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Even more radical new approaches to innovation with decentralized/distributed technology on the blockchain is The <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"http://enigma.media.mit.edu/enigma_full.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"http://enigma.media.mit.edu/enigma_full.pdf\">“MIT Enigma Machine”</a> a decentralized cloud platform with guaranteed privacy. Private data is stored, shared and analyzed without ever being fully revealed to any party. Secure multi-party computation all enabled by the blockchain, and a project inspired by Ethereum: <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"https://eprint.iacr.org/2015/675.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"https://eprint.iacr.org/2015/675.pdf\">“Hawk”</a>, a <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zero-knowledge_proof\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zero-knowledge_proof\">“zero knowledge protocol”</a> which allows a statement or transaction to be verified without conveying any information about it apart from the fact it’s true or adds up, thus retaining transactional privacy from the public’s view.</p>\r\n<p id=\"eeda\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">An implementation of technologies coordinated in an integrated fashion as described above, would open a variety of dimensions for innovation across financial, legal and civil services. <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"http://www.google.com/patents/US5086469\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"http://www.google.com/patents/US5086469\">“Selective Disclosure” </a>features, where the user can encrypt the attributes associated to their identity and selectively choose what information they wish to share; essentially our most sensitive data, could securely store; genomics, biometrics, financial data, keys, codes etc. Which could be linked to the identities in privacy-preserving ways which could prove to be crucial enablers, service enhancements, and competitive advantages for governments, banks, insurance providers, and public health institutions where the data attributes can be very personal and sensitive.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3 id=\"7b3b\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Intrepid Ventures invests, builds, and accelerates Blockchain and IoT companies solving the world’s most difficult problems.</h3>\r\n<p id=\"5014\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\"><em class=\"markup--em markup--p-em\">If you are interested in learning more about the rest of this whitepaper, our active projects in this space, how we can help your company design competitive new businesses with for your organization, or you’re an entrepreneur or technology leader looking for an interesting project to work for; please feel free to contact me here on </em><a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"https://hk.linkedin.com/in/collinthompson\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"https://hk.linkedin.com/in/collinthompson\"><em class=\"markup--em markup--p-em\">linkedin</em></a><em class=\"markup--em markup--p-em\"> or by email at </em><a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"https://medium.com/@collin_thompson/fintech-2-0-e17491431103\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"\"><em class=\"markup--em markup--p-em\">collin@intrepid.ventures.com</em></a></p>\r\n<p id=\"039a\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">The second half of this white paper explores solutions and uses cases that cover</p>\r\n<p id=\"1690\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\"><strong class=\"markup--strong markup--p-strong\">Blockchain identity, biometrics, and Multi-Factor identification across;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul class=\"postList\">\r\n	<li id=\"2a85\" class=\"graf--li graf-after--p\"><a class=\"markup--anchor markup--li-anchor\" href=\"http://www.ibm.com/mobilefirst/us/en/bring-your-own-device/byod.html\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"http://www.ibm.com/mobilefirst/us/en/bring-your-own-device/byod.html\">BYOD (Bring your own device)</a></li>\r\n	<li id=\"af45\" class=\"graf--li graf-after--li\">Payments (blockchain rails for transnational payments)</li>\r\n	<li id=\"13fe\" class=\"graf--li graf-after--li\"><a class=\"markup--anchor markup--li-anchor\" href=\"https://news.bitcoin.com/holy-trinity-blockchain-medical-records-wearable-tech/\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"https://news.bitcoin.com/holy-trinity-blockchain-medical-records-wearable-tech/\">Blockchain, Electronic Medical Records and Wearable Tech</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p id=\"03ad\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--li\"><strong class=\"markup--strong markup--p-strong\">How governments can improve legacy systems and provide better infrastructure for competitiveness and quality of life.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul class=\"postList\">\r\n	<li id=\"9eb4\" class=\"graf--li graf-after--p\"><a class=\"markup--anchor markup--li-anchor\" href=\"http://rossdawsonblog.com/weblog/archives/2014/09/new-layer-economy-enabled-m2m-payments-internet-things.html\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"http://rossdawsonblog.com/weblog/archives/2014/09/new-layer-economy-enabled-m2m-payments-internet-things.html\">Machine-to-machine payments</a> and smart merchants for the Internet of things</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p id=\"f714\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--li\"><strong class=\"markup--strong markup--p-strong\">How can banks provide modern peer-to-peer financial services that provide them with sustainability into the new economy.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<ul class=\"postList\">\r\n	<li id=\"0cda\" class=\"graf--li graf-after--p\"><a class=\"markup--anchor markup--li-anchor\" href=\"https://securityintelligence.com/how-banks-are-leveraging-bitcoin-and-blockchain-technologies/\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"https://securityintelligence.com/how-banks-are-leveraging-bitcoin-and-blockchain-technologies/\">Bank attested Identity services</a></li>\r\n	<li id=\"146a\" class=\"graf--li graf-after--li\">Credit scoring and reputation</li>\r\n	<li id=\"dba9\" class=\"graf--li graf-after--li\">Insurance</li>\r\n	<li id=\"0eca\" class=\"graf--li graf-after--li\">Payments/remittances; wallets, NFC, and reputation</li>\r\n	<li id=\"8c2d\" class=\"graf--li graf-after--li\">Credit (Mortgages/Car loans)</li>\r\n	<li id=\"6171\" class=\"graf--li graf-after--li graf--last\">Consumer credit (shopping/credit cards)</li>\r\n</ul>','FinTech 2.0: Identities, Blockchains And The Prospect For A Better Global Society','','inherit','closed','closed','','431-revision-v1','','','2016-02-18 09:40:12','2016-02-18 09:40:12','',431,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/431-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(433,8,'2016-02-18 09:41:48','2016-02-18 09:41:48','[agg_accordion multiselectable=\"false\"]\r\n\r\n[agg_accordion_item title=\"What is Backfeed?\"]\r\nBackfeed is an open-source startup that develops a social operating system for decentralized organizations, allowing for massive open source collaboration without central administration. We provide the infrastructure for decentralized cooperation, allowing large groups to create collectively and  share the value they\'ve generated according to contribution. Our goal is to enable anyone, anywhere to effectively collaborate with their peers without having to erect fixed hierarchies and rigid structures. The core of our decentralized governance tools and value distribution algorithm is the BACKFEED protocol, about which you can learn <a href=\"http://magazine.backfeed.cc/category/backfeed-101/\">here</a>.\r\n\r\n[/agg_accordion_item]\r\n\r\n[agg_accordion_item title=\"What is the BACKFEED Magazine?\"]\r\n\r\nDecentralization is one of the most important topics of our time with vast implications for every branch of social live; be it technology, economics, politics or culture. As an organization which recognizes the importance of this subject, and identifies it as one of the key elements for a prosperous future, we regard it as our responsibility to promote a wide ranging discussion about decentralization, the blockchain space and models for a collaborative economy; and you\'re invited to participate.\r\n\r\n<strong>We are a decentralized magazine</strong>, which essentially means that editing, writing and curation functions are delegated to the Backfeed community - which consists of our authors, readers and you, to the degree to which you’re interested in contributing. You can submit articles, rate the work of others and lead the discussion on topics brought forward here.\r\n\r\n[/agg_accordion_item]\r\n\r\n[agg_accordion_item title=\"Why should I be part of the BACKFEED magazine?\"]\r\n\r\nBecause it’s worth it!\r\n\r\nWe have a special algorithm that determines the value of each contribution - be it an article you’ve submitted, rating of such, an insightful comment or even the generation of traffic via shares and tweets. The value you’ve generated is transferred to you in form of Magazine-Tokens, which eventually might be worth real money. Read below how and when this happens.\r\n\r\n[/agg_accordion_item]\r\n\r\n[agg_accordion_item title=\"What are Magazine tokens good for?\"]\r\n\r\nTokens signify the value you’ve contributed to the Backfeed magazine in form of articles, ratings, comments and shares. They represent the stake you hold in the collective editing process of our crowd-sourced magazine.  At the moment they’re mainly symbolic, but we have serious plans to monetize them.\r\n\r\nOne of the obvious ways would be selling ads exclusively in exchange for tokens, which would mean that advertisers would have to purchase tokens from you in order to publish ads here - granting  them real monetary value. <b>But since we don’t like ads</b>, we’re currently looking for other creative ways to monetize tokens. Charging tokens as an access fee for various forms of premium content is an option - which, again, would require readers to purchase them from you, turning them into a value baring cryptocurrency.\r\n\r\nHowever, we strongly recommend holding on to your tokens. In the meantime, subscribe so we can keep you up to date on this topic.\r\n\r\n[/agg_accordion_item]\r\n\r\n[agg_accordion_item title=\"How does decentralized editing work?\"]\r\n\r\nFrom the way you rate the work of others and from the way others rate yours, our algorithm calculates a reputation score for you. This score determines how impactful you are in the editorial process. The more aligned you are with the backfeed community, the more influence you enjoy.\r\n\r\nThe reputation of all users is used by the algorithm to understand which contributions (submitted articles, comments, up/down votes) were valuable to the editorial process; tokens are then distributed to whomever lent a hand in a fruitful way.\r\n\r\nThis means that even your opinions on our articles, your up and down votes and your comments are worth (almost) genuine money (read above how) - after all, they’re what curates and edits this magazine.\r\n\r\nAt this point in time, the information gathered in the crowd-editing process is used to curate our front page and to decide which article will appear where. Further, more extended decentralized editing functions will be added later this year.\r\n\r\n[/agg_accordion_item]\r\n\r\n[agg_accordion_item title=\"How decentralized is the BACKFEED magazine?\"]\r\n\r\nOur end goal is to run the BACKFEED magazine as a fully operational decentralized organization, governed and edited by a vibrant online community without any central point of control and powered by our protocol - which is designed exactly to this end. At the moment the only truly decentralized function is the homepage layout and curation, along with the reputation system for contributors and their compensation with Magazine-tokens. Wider editing functions, such as the screening and editing of articles pre-publishing, the placement of picture-art and the choice of headlines, are being currently developed and will be online later this year.\r\n\r\n[/agg_accordion_item]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n[agg_accordion_item title=\"How do I participate?\"]\r\n\r\nFirst thing to do is to register. After that, all that\'s left is your natural interaction with the magazine: Rate articles according to your taste and to the degree to which you find them relevant or insightful. Share items on social media, post comments, rate and respond to comments of others, and, if you\'re in the mood - submit your own article. Every such action is evaluated, and if it was helpful to the editorial process you will be rewarded with tokens and your reputation is likely to increase.\r\n\r\n[/agg_accordion_item]\r\n\r\n[agg_accordion_item title=\"How does the reputation system work?\"]\r\n\r\nReputation is the measure of your alignment with the BACKFEED community. If your contributions are regarded as valuable by the community, your reputation increases, if they\'re seen as irrelevant, it decreases. - But that\'s not at all a reason to conform to the mainstream taste. On the contrary, if your taste deviates from the mainstream you might be the first one to spot an extraordinary contribution that was overseen by the crowd. Voting it up highlights it for the rest of the community, if it is then found to be useful, the algorithm compensates you to a much larger degree than those who just chase the herd. So be yourself and don\'t hesitate to express yourself.\r\n\r\nIf you want to learn more about the reputation system and the BACKFEED protocol in general, you can do so <a href=\"http://magazine.backfeed.cc/category/backfeed-101/\">here</a> and <a href=\"http://magazine.backfeed.cc/the-backfeed-protocol-an-introduction-for-mere-mortals/\">here</a>.\r\n\r\n[/agg_accordion_item]\r\n\r\n[agg_accordion_item title=\"What\'s the difference between reputation and tokens?\"]\r\n\r\n<b>Reputation</b> represents your influence on the editorial process, it is calculated from the way you rate the work of others and from the way others rate yours. The more aligned you are with the backfeed community, the more influence you enjoy.\r\n\r\n<b>Tokens</b> are your share of the value we’ve created together, they signify how useful your input was to the editorial process.\r\n\r\n<b>Tokens</b> are a transferable unit of value and function as a currency which can be bought and sold. <b>Reputation</b> is non-transferable and user specific.\r\n\r\n<b>Tokens</b> are generated every time a contribution was identified as valuable. Their total amount is not fixed and increases as long as new value is added to the system. <b>Reputation</b>, in contrast, is relative and fixed. There is a total amount of 100% influence in the system, of which your reputation represents the share you enjoy, so don\'t be upset if your rep. is only a fraction of a percent, this is pretty normal since, fortunately, we\'re a very large crowd.\r\n\r\n[/agg_accordion_item]\r\n\r\n[agg_accordion_item title=\"Why is my reputation so low?\"]\r\n\r\nReputation is relative and fixed. There is a total amount of 100% influence in the system, of which your reputation represents the share you enjoy, so don\'t be upset if your rep. is only a fraction of a percent, this is pretty normal since, fortunately, we\'re a very large crowd.\r\n\r\n[/agg_accordion_item]\r\n\r\n[/agg_accordion]','FAQ','','inherit','closed','closed','','380-revision-v1','','','2016-02-18 09:41:48','2016-02-18 09:41:48','',380,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/380-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(434,1,'2016-02-18 15:48:48','2016-02-18 15:48:48','A presentation by Primavera De Filippi (CNRS/Harvard) at <span id=\"eow-title\" class=\"watch-title \" dir=\"ltr\" title=\"Distributed Collobrative Organizations - COALA\'s Blockchain Workshops - Hong Kong 2015\">COALA\'s Blockchain Workshops - Hong Kong 2015</span>, followed by a panel hosting Simon de la Rouvière (Consensys), Primavera De Filippi (CNRS/Harvard). Moderated by Constance Choi (Seven Advisory)','Distributed Collaborative Organizations - COALA\'s Blockchain Workshops - Hong Kong 2015','','publish','closed','open','','distributed-collaborative-organizations-coalas-blockchain-workshops-hong-kong-2015','','','2016-03-09 09:36:35','2016-03-09 09:36:35','',0,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/?p=434',0,'post','',0),(435,8,'2016-02-18 15:48:09','2016-02-18 15:48:09','','Distributed Collobrative Organizations','','inherit','closed','closed','','distributed-collobrative-organizations','','','2016-02-18 15:48:09','2016-02-18 15:48:09','',434,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/Distributed-Collobrative-Organizations.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(436,8,'2016-02-18 15:48:28','2016-02-18 15:48:28','A presentation by Primavera De Filippi (CNRS/Harvard) at <span id=\"eow-title\" class=\"watch-title \" dir=\"ltr\" title=\"Distributed Collobrative Organizations - COALA\'s Blockchain Workshops - Hong Kong 2015\">COALA\'s Blockchain Workshops - Hong Kong 2015</span>, followed by a panel hosting Simon de la Rouvière (Consensys), Primavera De Filippi (CNRS/Harvard). Moderated by Constance Choi (Seven Advisory)','Distributed Collaborative Organizations - COALA\'s Blockchain Workshops - Hong Kong 2015','','inherit','closed','closed','','434-revision-v1','','','2016-02-18 15:48:28','2016-02-18 15:48:28','',434,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/434-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(437,9,'2016-02-21 15:53:08','2016-02-21 15:53:08','<p id=\"3388\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--h3\">There have been a lot of conversations about Bitcoin over the years. Is it a currency or an equity or a commodity? Is it a store of value? Is it a “settlement mechanism”? Is it not money at all, but merely an example of a decentralized application on the Blockchain? The short answer is: none of the above.</p>\r\n<p id=\"0bfa\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Bitcoin is a <strong class=\"markup--strong markup--p-strong\">self-organizing collective intelligence</strong>. As such, what it becomes is entirely a function of what it can do — that is, it is a function of the capacity of its collective intelligence to overcome the challenges that it encounters in its environment.</p>\r\n<p id=\"0225\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">In some sense, we’ve seen this sort of thing many times. Every “movement” or “<a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"http://kk.org/thetechnium/scenius-or-comm/\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"http://kk.org/thetechnium/scenius-or-comm/\">scenius</a>” (to use Brian Eno’s ingenious term for “collective genius”) is a form of self-organizing collective intelligence. The Punk Rock movement, skateboarding, Ruby on Rails. What makes Bitcoin important is that it represents a new mutation in self-organizing collective intelligence.</p>\r\n<p id=\"b61c\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">In order to explain what I mean by this, I’m first going to have to spend a few minutes laying out what I mean by self-organizing collective intelligence.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3 id=\"f460\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">The Development of Self Organizing Collective Intelligences (SOCI)</h3>\r\n<p id=\"298e\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">The basic dynamics of a SOCI is as follows:\r\nIt begins as some sort of attractor — some aesthetic sensibility or yearning — that is able to grab the attention and energy of some group of people. Generally one that is very vague and abstract. Some idea or notion that only makes sense to a relatively small group.</p>\r\n<p id=\"2620\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">But, and this is the key move, when those people apply their attention and energy to the SOCI, this makes it more real, easier for more people to grasp and to find interesting and valuable. Therefore, more attractive to more people and their attention and energy.</p>\r\n<p id=\"20eb\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Thus begins the generative loop: as the SOCI becomes more real and attracts more people it begins to encounter challenges. Maybe Impressionism is being rejected by the status quo and it needs to find some way to display itself. Maybe hand-coded HTML is too burdensome and clumsy and this SOCI needs to get easier to use.</p>\r\n<p id=\"7a6a\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">If the SOCI has enough capacity within its collective intelligence to resolve the challenge, it “levels up” and expands its ability to attract more attention and energy. If not, then it becomes somewhat bounded (at least for the present) and begins to find the limit of “what it is”.</p>\r\n<p id=\"2641\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Different SOCI will resolve challenges through different mechanisms. Some will form relatively centralized nodes (ICANN, Rolling Stone Magazine) that will <em class=\"markup--em markup--p-em\">accelerate</em> problem solving in certain areas — but at the cost of losing some of the generativity and flexibility of decentralization. Others will mutate and proliferate exploring their niche like a slime mold (Protestantism and electronic music might be a good examples here).</p>\r\n<p id=\"c46b\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">As the SOCI develops, the choices that it makes — the solutions that it crafts — become part of its core architecture. “Frozen accidents” in its development, these begin to shape and define its future paths, slowly accreting structure and topography as the SOCI moves from its vague, open and highly creative infancy through adolescence and finally into its mature, effective, but much less creative adulthood.</p>\r\n<p id=\"eb9e\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">In the end, the development of a SOCI is defined by the challenges it faces, its capacity to surmount those challenges, and the consequences of its solutions on its own further development.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3 id=\"71e9\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Bitcoin as a Self Organizing Collective Intelligences (SOCI)</h3>\r\n<p id=\"40f8\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Bitcoin is a SOCI. And its future will be determined precisely by the dynamic tension between the problems it faces and its capacity to solve those problems.</p>\r\n<p id=\"970f\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Over the years, Bitcoin has worked its way through a complicated childhood. It was able to attract the attention and energy of a core of developers who built software that made it possible for less technical folks to participate and apply their energy. It has been able to create online exchanges and marketplaces and then survive the collapse and redesign and collapse and redesign of these pieces of its architecture.</p>\r\n<p id=\"8e45\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">As it did this, it expanded its “reality” and attracted the attention and energy of more “professional” entrepreneurs and venture capitalists — whose work significantly expanded Bitcoin’s capacity (and birthed an offshoot in the form of the “blockchain SOCI).</p>\r\n<p id=\"c2e8\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Over the past year and a half it has struggled mightily with its most recent challenge: governance. For most of its developmental history, Bitcoin has been defined by two different governance mechanisms. The vast majority of the work has been highly decentralized — activities like wallet construction and exchange building that is entirely done “at the edge” and with little to no governance outside of simple architectural boundaries. The remainder of the work has been handled through an ad hoc oligarchy of the “Core Developers” who have been broadly able to maintain a highly technocratic coherence.</p>\r\n<p id=\"b849\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">This loose governance mechanism broke down as the collective intelligence couldn’t achieve coherence on purely technical grounds: two paths emerged that each presented valid, compelling and <em class=\"markup--em markup--p-em\">incompatible</em> attraction to different sensemaking elements of the collective intelligence. The result was the exploration of what might be a fundamental feature of this kind of SOCI’s governance — a “hard fork” where doctrinal and values differences are physically formalized into two separate code bases.</p>\r\n<p id=\"5ec9\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">So now we wait. Will the “hard fork” be the next level up for the Bitcoin SOCI and lead to an expansion of its ability to attract more intelligence? Or is this the hill that Bitcoin can’t climb and the beginning of its senescence?</p>\r\n<p id=\"9e15\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">This is the current question. But as interesting and important as this question is on its own terms, the real meaning of the Bitcoin experiment is deeper. This is because Bitcoin represents a <em class=\"markup--em markup--p-em\">new form</em> of SOCI and is the first real test of the power and adaptive capacity of this new SOCI organism.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3 id=\"b56e\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Bitcoin as a New form of self-organizing collective intelligence</h3>\r\n<p id=\"2729\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Lets step back and consider what the Bitcoin SOCI has already done.</p>\r\n<p id=\"9676\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Beginning with essentially no backing and no resources Bitcoin has been able to organically attract attention and energy to grow into something that includes dozens of exchanges in something like 40 different countries and a computational infrastructure that processes an astounding 14 Million PetaFLOPS.</p>\r\n<p id=\"8a40\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">And it has done this while innovating directly against one of the most fundamental components of our current social fabric: money. The beaches are littered with the bodies of well funded efforts to step into this space and, indeed, even a major victory like PayPal required the improbably combined genius of Peter Thiel, Elon Musk, Luke Nosek, Reid Hoffman and the rest of the much gloried <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PayPal_Mafia\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PayPal_Mafia\">PayPal Mafia</a> simply to carve out a nice niche in online payments.</p>\r\n<p id=\"074a\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">The Bitcoin SOCI has done this in merely seven short years.</p>\r\n<p id=\"93db\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">This is no ordinary SOCI. The deep importance if Bitcoin is that it represents the first example of an entirely new SOCI organism in our landscape. One that clearly represents a new kind of power and capability. In fact, one that might relate to our legacy forms of collective intelligence in the same way that Homo Sapiens related to Homo Neanderthalensis.</p>\r\n<p id=\"7333\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">What is the essence of this new form of collective intelligence that represents so much potential? My guess is that this can really only be answered with the benefit of hindsight. But I’ll venture a guess:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul class=\"postList\">\r\n	<li id=\"c963\" class=\"graf--li graf-after--p\">It is intrinsically global. More to the point, it is geographically unconstrained, and, therefore able to take advantage of any attention and energy anywhere in the world.</li>\r\n	<li id=\"1c22\" class=\"graf--li graf-after--li\">It is intrinsically virtual. In other words, it is able to connect with resources anywhere with minimal lag and at minimal cost.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p id=\"10eb\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--li\">These two features combine to mean that in principle this new form of SOCI can attract and utilize the total collective intelligence of the human species almost instantly. While in practice this level of concentrated collective intelligence isn’t likely to happen, the potential of tapping into and connecting precisely the girl in Phuket and the team in Slovenia, when where and how they are needed, is flat out revolutionary.</p>\r\n\r\n<ul class=\"postList\">\r\n	<li id=\"27ab\" class=\"graf--li graf-after--p\">It solves motivation, reward and collective action problems through an<em class=\"markup--em markup--li-em\">architecture</em> that is responsive to nuanced and changing value landscapes without being bottlenecked by concentrated (and, therefore, intelligence reducing) decision-makers.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p id=\"2951\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--li\">This needs to be unpacked. Consider digital SOCI like, say, WhatsApp, Facebook and Instagram. While these collective intelligences are both global and virtual, their ability to connect with, motivate and apply the attention and energy of their communities is either very narrow (you can contribute to the Instagram SOCI by uploading photos, liking and commenting them, but little more) or bottlenecked by a relatively small team of people who have exclusive power to adapt the architecture (like when the Facebook team added the ability to upload videos).</p>\r\n<p id=\"6aea\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Bitcoin-like SOCI use the technical capabilities of the blockchain, crypto-tokens and smart-contracts to provide a motivational architecture that can be highly adaptive to the real needs of the SOCI without bottlenecking through some concentrated control structure. As these techniques mature, they provide this new class of SOCI with an “executive function” that has little to no agency risk and can scale without creating a bottleneck on the SOCI.</p>\r\n<p id=\"78d1\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">To get a better sense of what I mean here, consider Bitcoin as an extremely early prototype of how this kind of motivational architecture can work. By linking “run hashing software” with “be the source of coin creation”, Bitcoin created an invitation to value contribution at an architectural level. Anyone who could understand and act on the invitation could participate without any human agents getting in the way to bottleneck the process.</p>\r\n<p id=\"3575\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">And by carefully wiring up difficulty and scarcity, Bitcoins became at least potentially appreciating assets — motivating anyone who could appreciate and act on this invitation to figure out how they could best give their value to the Bitcoin SOCI in exchange for increasingly valuable coins.</p>\r\n<p id=\"1184\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">While rough and coarse-grained, this approach worked. It was flat out <em class=\"markup--em markup--p-em\">brilliant</em> in incentivizing the construction and rollout of mining infrastructure, and as mentioned has delivered on a tremendous amount of creative activity.</p>\r\n<p id=\"60f2\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Of course, the Bitcoin approach has known issues. High volatility, a dependence on risk seeking speculation, too much concentration in the hands of early adopters, coarse-grained focus on mining, etc. Arguably, these design elements limit the effectiveness of the SOCI to attract and deploy collective intelligence and, therefore, its overall potential.</p>\r\n<p id=\"6305\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">With regard to the Bitcoin SOCI in particular, the future is uncertain. Will it overcome its governance challenges and emerge on the other side with still more collective intelligence? I honestly have no idea, I suspect it will, but these moments are always deeply uncertain.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_441\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"468\"]<img class=\"wp-image-441\" src=\"http://magazine.backfeed.cc/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/MTgox-1024x519.png\" alt=\"MTgox\" width=\"468\" height=\"237\" /> The MtGox Crash, April 2013.[/caption]\r\n<p id=\"2912\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">If it does, however, it will come out the other end much stronger than it has been so far. Governance is a major challenge. If Bitcoin survives this current crisis, my bet is that the collective intelligence will focus its efforts on governance much like it has on past crises like the Mt. Gox collapse — and the result will be a much, much more capable SOCI.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3 id=\"0659\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">The Future of Self Organizing Collective Intelligences</h3>\r\n<p id=\"c4cc\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Regardless of the specific result of the Bitcoin experiment, we are clearly in the middle of a new era. As I discussed in <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"http://magazine.backfeed.cc/the-future-of-organization/\" data-href=\"https://medium.com/deep-code/the-future-of-organization-b26219e5fc95#.c6x7qtfzq\">The Future of Organization</a>, a lot of smart people are currently hard at work understanding, generalizing and optimizing the deep code of these new forms of collective intelligence.</p>\r\n<p id=\"228a\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">The limitations of Bitcoin’s approach to motivation and collective action are well understood and new technical layers like <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"https://www.ethereum.org/\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"https://www.ethereum.org/\">Ethereum’s</a> smart contracts and <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"http://backfeed.cc/\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"http://backfeed.cc/\">Backfeed’s</a> distributed governance system magnify the potential intelligence of this kind of SOCI at least as much as the neocortex magnified the intelligence of the mammalian brain.</p>\r\n<p id=\"27f8\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">I really wish the reality and importance of this new frontier were more broadly understood. My sense is that over just the next five years this new form of SOCI will go through its gestation, birthing and childhood development stages. The result will be a form of collective intelligence that is so much more capable than anything in the current environment, that it will sweep away even the most powerful contemporary collective intelligences (in particular both corporations and nation states) in establishing itself as the new dominant form of collective intelligence on the Earth.</p>\r\n<p id=\"08d2\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p graf--last\">And whoever gets there first will “win” in a fashion that is rarely seen in history.\r\n\r\nThis article was republished from Jordan Greenhalls\' <a href=\"https://medium.com/deep-code/lets-get-this-straight-bitcoin-is-an-experiment-in-self-organizing-collective-intelligence-52d78212c5e6#.cjopmo7h3\">blog on Medium</a></p>','Lets get this straight, Bitcoin is an experiment in self-organizing collective intelligence.','','publish','closed','open','','lets-get-this-straight-bitcoin-is-an-experiment-in-self-organizing-collective-intelligence','','','2016-03-09 09:11:03','2016-03-09 09:11:03','',0,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/?p=437',0,'post','',0),(438,8,'2016-02-21 15:25:42','2016-02-21 15:25:42','','group02','','inherit','closed','closed','','group02','','','2016-02-21 15:25:42','2016-02-21 15:25:42','',437,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/group02.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(439,8,'2016-02-21 15:25:48','2016-02-21 15:25:48','<p id=\"3388\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--h3\">There have been a lot of conversations about Bitcoin over the years. Is it a currency or an equity or a commodity? Is it a store of value? Is it a “settlement mechanism”? Is it not money at all, but merely an example of a decentralized application on the Blockchain? The short answer is: none of the above.</p>\r\n<p id=\"0bfa\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Bitcoin is a <strong class=\"markup--strong markup--p-strong\">self-organizing collective intelligence</strong>. As such, what it becomes is entirely a function of what it can do — that is, it is a function of the capacity of its collective intelligence to overcome the challenges that it encounters in its environment.</p>\r\n<p id=\"0225\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">In some sense, we’ve seen this sort of thing many times. Every “movement” or “<a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"http://kk.org/thetechnium/scenius-or-comm/\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"http://kk.org/thetechnium/scenius-or-comm/\">scenius</a>” (to use Brian Eno’s ingenious term for “collective genius”) is a form of self-organizing collective intelligence. The Punk Rock movement, skateboarding, Ruby on Rails. What makes Bitcoin important is that it represents a new mutation in self-organizing collective intelligence.</p>\r\n<p id=\"b61c\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">In order to explain what I mean by this, I’m first going to have to spend a few minutes laying out what I mean by self-organizing collective intelligence.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3 id=\"f460\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">The Development of Self Organizing Collective Intelligences (SOCI)</h3>\r\n<p id=\"298e\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">The basic dynamics of a SOCI is as follows:\r\nIt begins as some sort of attractor — some aesthetic sensibility or yearning — that is able to grab the attention and energy of some group of people. Generally one that is very vague and abstract. Some idea or notion that only makes sense to a relatively small group.</p>\r\n<p id=\"2620\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">But, and this is the key move, when those people apply their attention and energy to the SOCI, this makes it more real, easier for more people to grasp and to find interesting and valuable. Therefore, more attractive to more people and their attention and energy.</p>\r\n<p id=\"20eb\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Thus begins the generative loop: as the SOCI becomes more real and attracts more people it begins to encounter challenges. Maybe Impressionism is being rejected by the status quo and it needs to find some way to display itself. Maybe hand-coded HTML is too burdensome and clumsy and this SOCI needs to get easier to use.</p>\r\n<p id=\"7a6a\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">If the SOCI has enough capacity within its collective intelligence to resolve the challenge, it “levels up” and expands its ability to attract more attention and energy. If not, then it becomes somewhat bounded (at least for the present) and begins to find the limit of “what it is”.</p>\r\n<p id=\"2641\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Different SOCI will resolve challenges through different mechanisms. Some will form relatively centralized nodes (ICANN, Rolling Stone Magazine) that will <em class=\"markup--em markup--p-em\">accelerate</em> problem solving in certain areas — but at the cost of losing some of the generativity and flexibility of decentralization. Others will mutate and proliferate exploring their niche like a slime mold (Protestantism and electronic music might be a good examples here).</p>\r\n<p id=\"c46b\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">As the SOCI develops, the choices that it makes — the solutions that it crafts — become part of its core architecture. “Frozen accidents” in its development, these begin to shape and define its future paths, slowly accreting structure and topography as the SOCI moves from its vague, open and highly creative infancy through adolescence and finally into its mature, effective, but much less creative adulthood.</p>\r\n<p id=\"eb9e\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">In the end, the development of a SOCI is defined by the challenges it faces, its capacity to surmount those challenges, and the consequences of its solutions on its own further development.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3 id=\"71e9\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Bitcoin as a Self Organizing Collective Intelligences (SOCI)</h3>\r\n<p id=\"40f8\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Bitcoin is a SOCI. And its future will be determined precisely by the dynamic tension between the problems it faces and its capacity to solve those problems.</p>\r\n<p id=\"970f\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Over the years, Bitcoin has worked its way through a complicated childhood. It was able to attract the attention and energy of a core of developers who built software that made it possible for less technical folks to participate and apply their energy. It has been able to create online exchanges and marketplaces and then survive the collapse and redesign and collapse and redesign of these pieces of its architecture.</p>\r\n<p id=\"8e45\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">As it did this, it expanded its “reality” and attracted the attention and energy of more “professional” entrepreneurs and venture capitalists — whose work significantly expanded Bitcoin’s capacity (and birthed an offshoot in the form of the “blockchain SOCI).</p>\r\n<p id=\"c2e8\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Over the past year and a half it has struggled mightily with its most recent challenge: governance. For most of its developmental history, Bitcoin has been defined by two different governance mechanisms. The vast majority of the work has been highly decentralized — activities like wallet construction and exchange building that is entirely done “at the edge” and with little to no governance outside of simple architectural boundaries. The remainder of the work has been handled through an ad hoc oligarchy of the “Core Developers” who have been broadly able to maintain a highly technocratic coherence.</p>\r\n<p id=\"b849\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">This loose governance mechanism broke down as the collective intelligence couldn’t achieve coherence on purely technical grounds: two paths emerged that each presented valid, compelling and <em class=\"markup--em markup--p-em\">incompatible</em> attraction to different sensemaking elements of the collective intelligence. The result was the exploration of what might be a fundamental feature of this kind of SOCI’s governance — a “hard fork” where doctrinal and values differences are physically formalized into two separate code bases.</p>\r\n<p id=\"5ec9\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">So now we wait. Will the “hard fork” be the next level up for the Bitcoin SOCI and lead to an expansion of its ability to attract more intelligence? Or is this the hill that Bitcoin can’t climb and the beginning of its senescence?</p>\r\n<p id=\"9e15\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">This is the current question. But as interesting and important as this question is on its own terms, the real meaning of the Bitcoin experiment is deeper. This is because Bitcoin represents a <em class=\"markup--em markup--p-em\">new form</em> of SOCI and is the first real test of the power and adaptive capacity of this new SOCI organism.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3 id=\"b56e\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Bitcoin as a New form of self-organizing collective intelligence</h3>\r\n<p id=\"2729\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Lets step back and consider what the Bitcoin SOCI has already done.</p>\r\n<p id=\"9676\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Beginning with essentially no backing and no resources Bitcoin has been able to organically attract attention and energy to grow into something that includes dozens of exchanges in something like 40 different countries and a computational infrastructure that processes an astounding 14 Million PetaFLOPS.</p>\r\n<p id=\"8a40\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">And it has done this while innovating directly against one of the most fundamental components of our current social fabric: money. The beaches are littered with the bodies of well funded efforts to step into this space and, indeed, even a major victory like PayPal required the improbably combined genius of Peter Thiel, Elon Musk, Luke Nosek, Reid Hoffman and the rest of the much gloried <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PayPal_Mafia\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PayPal_Mafia\">PayPal Mafia</a> simply to carve out a nice niche in online payments.</p>\r\n<p id=\"074a\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">The Bitcoin SOCI has done this in merely seven short years.</p>\r\n<p id=\"93db\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">This is no ordinary SOCI. The deep importance if Bitcoin is that it represents the first example of an entirely new SOCI organism in our landscape. One that clearly represents a new kind of power and capability. In fact, one that might relate to our legacy forms of collective intelligence in the same way that Homo Sapiens related to Homo Neanderthalensis.</p>\r\n<p id=\"7333\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">What is the essence of this new form of collective intelligence that represents so much potential? My guess is that this can really only be answered with the benefit of hindsight. But I’ll venture a guess:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul class=\"postList\">\r\n	<li id=\"c963\" class=\"graf--li graf-after--p\">It is intrinsically global. More to the point, it is geographically unconstrained, and, therefore able to take advantage of any attention and energy anywhere in the world.</li>\r\n	<li id=\"1c22\" class=\"graf--li graf-after--li\">It is intrinsically virtual. In other words, it is able to connect with resources anywhere with minimal lag and at minimal cost.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p id=\"10eb\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--li\">These two features combine to mean that in principle this new form of SOCI can attract and utilize the total collective intelligence of the human species almost instantly. While in practice this level of concentrated collective intelligence isn’t likely to happen, the potential of tapping into and connecting precisely the girl in Phuket and the team in Slovenia, when where and how they are needed, is flat out revolutionary.</p>\r\n\r\n<ul class=\"postList\">\r\n	<li id=\"27ab\" class=\"graf--li graf-after--p\">It solves motivation, reward and collective action problems through an<em class=\"markup--em markup--li-em\">architecture</em> that is responsive to nuanced and changing value landscapes without being bottlenecked by concentrated (and, therefore, intelligence reducing) decision-makers.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p id=\"2951\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--li\">This needs to be unpacked. Consider digital SOCI like, say, WhatsApp, Facebook and Instagram. While these collective intelligences are both global and virtual, their ability to connect with, motivate and apply the attention and energy of their communities is either very narrow (you can contribute to the Instagram SOCI by uploading photos, liking and commenting them, but little more) or bottlenecked by a relatively small team of people who have exclusive power to adapt the architecture (like when the Facebook team added the ability to upload videos).</p>\r\n<p id=\"6aea\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Bitcoin-like SOCI use the technical capabilities of the blockchain, crypto-tokens and smart-contracts to provide a motivational architecture that can be highly adaptive to the real needs of the SOCI without bottlenecking through some concentrated control structure. As these techniques mature, they provide this new class of SOCI with an “executive function” that has little to no agency risk and can scale without creating a bottleneck on the SOCI.</p>\r\n<p id=\"78d1\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">To get a better sense of what I mean here, consider Bitcoin as an extremely early prototype of how this kind of motivational architecture can work. By linking “run hashing software” with “be the source of coin creation”, Bitcoin created an invitation to value contribution at an architectural level. Anyone who could understand and act on the invitation could participate without any human agents getting in the way to bottleneck the process.</p>\r\n<p id=\"3575\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">And by carefully wiring up difficulty and scarcity, Bitcoins became at least potentially appreciating assets — motivating anyone who could appreciate and act on this invitation to figure out how they could best give their value to the Bitcoin SOCI in exchange for increasingly valuable coins.</p>\r\n<p id=\"1184\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">While rough and coarse-grained, this approach worked. It was flat out <em class=\"markup--em markup--p-em\">brilliant</em> in incentivizing the construction and rollout of mining infrastructure, and as mentioned has delivered on a tremendous amount of creative activity.</p>\r\n<p id=\"60f2\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Of course, the Bitcoin approach has known issues. High volatility, a dependence on risk seeking speculation, too much concentration in the hands of early adopters, coarse-grained focus on mining, etc. Arguably, these design elements limit the effectiveness of the SOCI to attract and deploy collective intelligence and, therefore, its overall potential.</p>\r\n<p id=\"6305\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">With regard to the Bitcoin SOCI in particular, the future is uncertain. Will it overcome its governance challenges and emerge on the other side with still more collective intelligence? I honestly have no idea, I suspect it will, but these moments are always deeply uncertain.</p>\r\n<p id=\"2912\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">If it does, however, it will come out the other end much stronger than it has been so far. Governance is a major challenge. If Bitcoin survives this current crisis, my bet is that the collective intelligence will focus its efforts on governance much like it has on past crises like the Mt. Gox collapse — and the result will be a much, much more capable SOCI.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3 id=\"0659\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">The Future of Self Organizing Collective Intelligences</h3>\r\n<p id=\"c4cc\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Regardless of the specific result of the Bitcoin experiment, we are clearly in the middle of a new era. As I discussed in <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"http://magazine.backfeed.cc/the-future-of-organization/\" data-href=\"https://medium.com/deep-code/the-future-of-organization-b26219e5fc95#.c6x7qtfzq\">The Future of Organization</a>, a lot of smart people are currently hard at work understanding, generalizing and optimizing the deep code of these new forms of collective intelligence.</p>\r\n<p id=\"228a\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">The limitations of Bitcoin’s approach to motivation and collective action are well understood and new technical layers like <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"https://www.ethereum.org/\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"https://www.ethereum.org/\">Ethereum’s</a> smart contracts and <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"http://backfeed.cc/\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"http://backfeed.cc/\">Backfeed’s</a> distributed governance system magnify the potential intelligence of this kind of SOCI at least as much as the neocortex magnified the intelligence of the mammalian brain.</p>\r\n<p id=\"27f8\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">I really wish the reality and importance of this new frontier were more broadly understood. My sense is that over just the next five years this new form of SOCI will go through its gestation, birthing and childhood development stages. The result will be a form of collective intelligence that is so much more capable than anything in the current environment, that it will sweep away even the most powerful contemporary collective intelligences (in particular both corporations and nation states) in establishing itself as the new dominant form of collective intelligence on the Earth.</p>\r\n<p id=\"08d2\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p graf--last\">And whoever gets there first will “win” in a fashion that is rarely seen in history.</p>','Lets get this straight, Bitcoin is an experiment in self-organizing collective intelligence.','','inherit','closed','closed','','437-revision-v1','','','2016-02-21 15:25:48','2016-02-21 15:25:48','',437,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/437-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(440,8,'2016-02-21 15:26:18','2016-02-21 15:26:18','','group01','','inherit','closed','closed','','group01','','','2016-02-21 15:26:18','2016-02-21 15:26:18','',437,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/group01.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(441,8,'2016-02-21 15:35:54','2016-02-21 15:35:54','','MTgox','','inherit','closed','closed','','mtgox','','','2016-02-21 15:35:54','2016-02-21 15:35:54','',437,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/MTgox.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(442,8,'2016-02-21 15:40:00','2016-02-21 15:40:00','<p id=\"3388\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--h3\">There have been a lot of conversations about Bitcoin over the years. Is it a currency or an equity or a commodity? Is it a store of value? Is it a “settlement mechanism”? Is it not money at all, but merely an example of a decentralized application on the Blockchain? The short answer is: none of the above.</p>\r\n<p id=\"0bfa\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Bitcoin is a <strong class=\"markup--strong markup--p-strong\">self-organizing collective intelligence</strong>. As such, what it becomes is entirely a function of what it can do — that is, it is a function of the capacity of its collective intelligence to overcome the challenges that it encounters in its environment.</p>\r\n<p id=\"0225\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">In some sense, we’ve seen this sort of thing many times. Every “movement” or “<a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"http://kk.org/thetechnium/scenius-or-comm/\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"http://kk.org/thetechnium/scenius-or-comm/\">scenius</a>” (to use Brian Eno’s ingenious term for “collective genius”) is a form of self-organizing collective intelligence. The Punk Rock movement, skateboarding, Ruby on Rails. What makes Bitcoin important is that it represents a new mutation in self-organizing collective intelligence.</p>\r\n<p id=\"b61c\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">In order to explain what I mean by this, I’m first going to have to spend a few minutes laying out what I mean by self-organizing collective intelligence.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3 id=\"f460\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">The Development of Self Organizing Collective Intelligences (SOCI)</h3>\r\n<p id=\"298e\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">The basic dynamics of a SOCI is as follows:\r\nIt begins as some sort of attractor — some aesthetic sensibility or yearning — that is able to grab the attention and energy of some group of people. Generally one that is very vague and abstract. Some idea or notion that only makes sense to a relatively small group.</p>\r\n<p id=\"2620\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">But, and this is the key move, when those people apply their attention and energy to the SOCI, this makes it more real, easier for more people to grasp and to find interesting and valuable. Therefore, more attractive to more people and their attention and energy.</p>\r\n<p id=\"20eb\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Thus begins the generative loop: as the SOCI becomes more real and attracts more people it begins to encounter challenges. Maybe Impressionism is being rejected by the status quo and it needs to find some way to display itself. Maybe hand-coded HTML is too burdensome and clumsy and this SOCI needs to get easier to use.</p>\r\n<p id=\"7a6a\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">If the SOCI has enough capacity within its collective intelligence to resolve the challenge, it “levels up” and expands its ability to attract more attention and energy. If not, then it becomes somewhat bounded (at least for the present) and begins to find the limit of “what it is”.</p>\r\n<p id=\"2641\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Different SOCI will resolve challenges through different mechanisms. Some will form relatively centralized nodes (ICANN, Rolling Stone Magazine) that will <em class=\"markup--em markup--p-em\">accelerate</em> problem solving in certain areas — but at the cost of losing some of the generativity and flexibility of decentralization. Others will mutate and proliferate exploring their niche like a slime mold (Protestantism and electronic music might be a good examples here).</p>\r\n<p id=\"c46b\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">As the SOCI develops, the choices that it makes — the solutions that it crafts — become part of its core architecture. “Frozen accidents” in its development, these begin to shape and define its future paths, slowly accreting structure and topography as the SOCI moves from its vague, open and highly creative infancy through adolescence and finally into its mature, effective, but much less creative adulthood.</p>\r\n<p id=\"eb9e\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">In the end, the development of a SOCI is defined by the challenges it faces, its capacity to surmount those challenges, and the consequences of its solutions on its own further development.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3 id=\"71e9\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Bitcoin as a Self Organizing Collective Intelligences (SOCI)</h3>\r\n<p id=\"40f8\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Bitcoin is a SOCI. And its future will be determined precisely by the dynamic tension between the problems it faces and its capacity to solve those problems.</p>\r\n<p id=\"970f\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Over the years, Bitcoin has worked its way through a complicated childhood. It was able to attract the attention and energy of a core of developers who built software that made it possible for less technical folks to participate and apply their energy. It has been able to create online exchanges and marketplaces and then survive the collapse and redesign and collapse and redesign of these pieces of its architecture.</p>\r\n<p id=\"8e45\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">As it did this, it expanded its “reality” and attracted the attention and energy of more “professional” entrepreneurs and venture capitalists — whose work significantly expanded Bitcoin’s capacity (and birthed an offshoot in the form of the “blockchain SOCI).</p>\r\n<p id=\"c2e8\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Over the past year and a half it has struggled mightily with its most recent challenge: governance. For most of its developmental history, Bitcoin has been defined by two different governance mechanisms. The vast majority of the work has been highly decentralized — activities like wallet construction and exchange building that is entirely done “at the edge” and with little to no governance outside of simple architectural boundaries. The remainder of the work has been handled through an ad hoc oligarchy of the “Core Developers” who have been broadly able to maintain a highly technocratic coherence.</p>\r\n<p id=\"b849\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">This loose governance mechanism broke down as the collective intelligence couldn’t achieve coherence on purely technical grounds: two paths emerged that each presented valid, compelling and <em class=\"markup--em markup--p-em\">incompatible</em> attraction to different sensemaking elements of the collective intelligence. The result was the exploration of what might be a fundamental feature of this kind of SOCI’s governance — a “hard fork” where doctrinal and values differences are physically formalized into two separate code bases.</p>\r\n<p id=\"5ec9\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">So now we wait. Will the “hard fork” be the next level up for the Bitcoin SOCI and lead to an expansion of its ability to attract more intelligence? Or is this the hill that Bitcoin can’t climb and the beginning of its senescence?</p>\r\n<p id=\"9e15\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">This is the current question. But as interesting and important as this question is on its own terms, the real meaning of the Bitcoin experiment is deeper. This is because Bitcoin represents a <em class=\"markup--em markup--p-em\">new form</em> of SOCI and is the first real test of the power and adaptive capacity of this new SOCI organism.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3 id=\"b56e\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Bitcoin as a New form of self-organizing collective intelligence</h3>\r\n<p id=\"2729\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Lets step back and consider what the Bitcoin SOCI has already done.</p>\r\n<p id=\"9676\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Beginning with essentially no backing and no resources Bitcoin has been able to organically attract attention and energy to grow into something that includes dozens of exchanges in something like 40 different countries and a computational infrastructure that processes an astounding 14 Million PetaFLOPS.</p>\r\n<p id=\"8a40\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">And it has done this while innovating directly against one of the most fundamental components of our current social fabric: money. The beaches are littered with the bodies of well funded efforts to step into this space and, indeed, even a major victory like PayPal required the improbably combined genius of Peter Thiel, Elon Musk, Luke Nosek, Reid Hoffman and the rest of the much gloried <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PayPal_Mafia\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PayPal_Mafia\">PayPal Mafia</a> simply to carve out a nice niche in online payments.</p>\r\n<p id=\"074a\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">The Bitcoin SOCI has done this in merely seven short years.</p>\r\n<p id=\"93db\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">This is no ordinary SOCI. The deep importance if Bitcoin is that it represents the first example of an entirely new SOCI organism in our landscape. One that clearly represents a new kind of power and capability. In fact, one that might relate to our legacy forms of collective intelligence in the same way that Homo Sapiens related to Homo Neanderthalensis.</p>\r\n<p id=\"7333\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">What is the essence of this new form of collective intelligence that represents so much potential? My guess is that this can really only be answered with the benefit of hindsight. But I’ll venture a guess:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul class=\"postList\">\r\n	<li id=\"c963\" class=\"graf--li graf-after--p\">It is intrinsically global. More to the point, it is geographically unconstrained, and, therefore able to take advantage of any attention and energy anywhere in the world.</li>\r\n	<li id=\"1c22\" class=\"graf--li graf-after--li\">It is intrinsically virtual. In other words, it is able to connect with resources anywhere with minimal lag and at minimal cost.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p id=\"10eb\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--li\">These two features combine to mean that in principle this new form of SOCI can attract and utilize the total collective intelligence of the human species almost instantly. While in practice this level of concentrated collective intelligence isn’t likely to happen, the potential of tapping into and connecting precisely the girl in Phuket and the team in Slovenia, when where and how they are needed, is flat out revolutionary.</p>\r\n\r\n<ul class=\"postList\">\r\n	<li id=\"27ab\" class=\"graf--li graf-after--p\">It solves motivation, reward and collective action problems through an<em class=\"markup--em markup--li-em\">architecture</em> that is responsive to nuanced and changing value landscapes without being bottlenecked by concentrated (and, therefore, intelligence reducing) decision-makers.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p id=\"2951\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--li\">This needs to be unpacked. Consider digital SOCI like, say, WhatsApp, Facebook and Instagram. While these collective intelligences are both global and virtual, their ability to connect with, motivate and apply the attention and energy of their communities is either very narrow (you can contribute to the Instagram SOCI by uploading photos, liking and commenting them, but little more) or bottlenecked by a relatively small team of people who have exclusive power to adapt the architecture (like when the Facebook team added the ability to upload videos).</p>\r\n<p id=\"6aea\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Bitcoin-like SOCI use the technical capabilities of the blockchain, crypto-tokens and smart-contracts to provide a motivational architecture that can be highly adaptive to the real needs of the SOCI without bottlenecking through some concentrated control structure. As these techniques mature, they provide this new class of SOCI with an “executive function” that has little to no agency risk and can scale without creating a bottleneck on the SOCI.</p>\r\n<p id=\"78d1\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">To get a better sense of what I mean here, consider Bitcoin as an extremely early prototype of how this kind of motivational architecture can work. By linking “run hashing software” with “be the source of coin creation”, Bitcoin created an invitation to value contribution at an architectural level. Anyone who could understand and act on the invitation could participate without any human agents getting in the way to bottleneck the process.</p>\r\n<p id=\"3575\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">And by carefully wiring up difficulty and scarcity, Bitcoins became at least potentially appreciating assets — motivating anyone who could appreciate and act on this invitation to figure out how they could best give their value to the Bitcoin SOCI in exchange for increasingly valuable coins.</p>\r\n<p id=\"1184\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">While rough and coarse-grained, this approach worked. It was flat out <em class=\"markup--em markup--p-em\">brilliant</em> in incentivizing the construction and rollout of mining infrastructure, and as mentioned has delivered on a tremendous amount of creative activity.</p>\r\n<p id=\"60f2\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Of course, the Bitcoin approach has known issues. High volatility, a dependence on risk seeking speculation, too much concentration in the hands of early adopters, coarse-grained focus on mining, etc. Arguably, these design elements limit the effectiveness of the SOCI to attract and deploy collective intelligence and, therefore, its overall potential.</p>\r\n<p id=\"6305\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">With regard to the Bitcoin SOCI in particular, the future is uncertain. Will it overcome its governance challenges and emerge on the other side with still more collective intelligence? I honestly have no idea, I suspect it will, but these moments are always deeply uncertain.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_441\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"468\"]<img class=\"wp-image-441\" src=\"http://magazine.backfeed.cc/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/MTgox-1024x519.png\" alt=\"MTgox\" width=\"468\" height=\"237\" /> The MtGox Crash, April 2013.[/caption]\r\n<p id=\"2912\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">If it does, however, it will come out the other end much stronger than it has been so far. Governance is a major challenge. If Bitcoin survives this current crisis, my bet is that the collective intelligence will focus its efforts on governance much like it has on past crises like the Mt. Gox collapse — and the result will be a much, much more capable SOCI.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3 id=\"0659\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">The Future of Self Organizing Collective Intelligences</h3>\r\n<p id=\"c4cc\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">Regardless of the specific result of the Bitcoin experiment, we are clearly in the middle of a new era. As I discussed in <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"http://magazine.backfeed.cc/the-future-of-organization/\" data-href=\"https://medium.com/deep-code/the-future-of-organization-b26219e5fc95#.c6x7qtfzq\">The Future of Organization</a>, a lot of smart people are currently hard at work understanding, generalizing and optimizing the deep code of these new forms of collective intelligence.</p>\r\n<p id=\"228a\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">The limitations of Bitcoin’s approach to motivation and collective action are well understood and new technical layers like <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"https://www.ethereum.org/\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"https://www.ethereum.org/\">Ethereum’s</a> smart contracts and <a class=\"markup--anchor markup--p-anchor\" href=\"http://backfeed.cc/\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-href=\"http://backfeed.cc/\">Backfeed’s</a> distributed governance system magnify the potential intelligence of this kind of SOCI at least as much as the neocortex magnified the intelligence of the mammalian brain.</p>\r\n<p id=\"27f8\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p\">I really wish the reality and importance of this new frontier were more broadly understood. My sense is that over just the next five years this new form of SOCI will go through its gestation, birthing and childhood development stages. The result will be a form of collective intelligence that is so much more capable than anything in the current environment, that it will sweep away even the most powerful contemporary collective intelligences (in particular both corporations and nation states) in establishing itself as the new dominant form of collective intelligence on the Earth.</p>\r\n<p id=\"08d2\" class=\"graf--p graf-after--p graf--last\">And whoever gets there first will “win” in a fashion that is rarely seen in history.\r\n\r\nThis article was republished from Jordan Grenhalls\' <a href=\"https://medium.com/deep-code/lets-get-this-straight-bitcoin-is-an-experiment-in-self-organizing-collective-intelligence-52d78212c5e6#.cjopmo7h3\">blog on medium</a></p>','Lets get this straight, Bitcoin is an experiment in self-organizing collective intelligence.','','inherit','closed','closed','','437-revision-v1','','','2016-02-21 15:40:00','2016-02-21 15:40:00','',437,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/437-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(443,8,'2016-02-22 15:52:58','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','The Fallacy Of Getting Rid Of Humans','','draft','closed','open','','','','','2016-02-22 15:52:58','2016-02-22 15:52:58','',0,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/?p=443',0,'post','',0),(444,15,'2016-02-23 16:26:12','2016-02-23 16:26:12','The last year in Bitcoin has seen an effective stranglehold on the development and growth of the ecosystem that has centered around the \"block size debate\", as we see everyone who\'s anyone in fintech move almost wholesale towards this newly discovered \"blockchain\" thing.\r\n\r\nWhat may seem like a technical issue is really anything but. What we see is a break in consensus about what Bitcoin is, what it should be, and what role centralised organisations play in the Bitcoin ecosystem, forced by a stall in growth and increased competition from alternative solutions. This manifested itself as a seemingly technical debate, mostly involving the developers of Bitcoin, but at its core it\'s a political discussion.\r\n\r\nThere are a few parties at play:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Bitcoin Miners who actually add transactions into blocks</li>\r\n	<li>The Bitcoin payments camp, who want to see Bitcoin used for payments as a credit card replacement</li>\r\n	<li>Off-chain Bitcoin companies who profit from Bitcoin transactions that don\'t take place on the Blockchain</li>\r\n	<li>Decentralisation idealists who see Bitcoin\'s decentralised nature as sacred, not to be compromised for the sake of lower cost or increased utility</li>\r\n	<li>Blockchain application developers, who want to build on-blockchain applications</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThough these groups have their own perspective, when it comes down to it, the debate is one over increased centralisation and increased utility, or decreased centralisation and decreased utility; it\'s only possible to increase blockchain throughput by reducing the number of nodes in the network.\r\n\r\nHowever, the point of this article isn\'t to become yet another one about the block size, but to investigate Bitcoin\'s growth pains in context.\r\n<h2 id=\"bitcoinasanorganisation\">Bitcoin as an Organisation</h2>\r\nIt\'s important not to look at Bitcoin and it\'s ecosystem as something completely new. While it\'s a unique combination, there have been many projects before it with similar characteristics, and many new organisations after. Bitcoin is an open source project, but it has some characteristics that are traditionally associated with Public Companies and Startups.\r\n\r\nLike an open source project, the \"organisation\" is highly dis-organised, distributed across the globe, <span style=\"color: #ff0000;\">has a lot of users(developers?), a proportionally small number of users </span>and capital behind core development.\r\n\r\nLike a startup, it\'s been a new technology trying to get adoption, and it\'s been through some extremely volatile stages. A startup needs technology development, sales and marketing, a leader and a vision. I\'d say it\'s graduated from this phase of it\'s life but not necessarily successfully.\r\n\r\nA fun exercise is to look at tech company organisational structures and think about how Bitcoin might compare:\r\n<p class=\"article-image\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://markwilcox.com/content/images/2016/02/2011-06-27_organizational_charts.png\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\nBut it\'s also been like a public company in that through it\'s whole life it\'s been a \"publicly tradeable digital asset\". Maybe less so compared to newer cryptocurrencies that are coming to life in an ecosystem that is already accepting of and interested in alternative \"stocks\". In the early life of Bitcoin there wasn\'t that demand.\r\n\r\nBitcoin\'s development is not dissimilar to other open source projects. The most evolved and long-lasting open source projects tend to have a <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Benevolent_dictator_for_life\">Benevolent Dictator for Life</a>, which Bitcoin has no longer.\r\n\r\nIf you look at open source communities of high economic value, without a strong leader, the most obvious comparison to make is OpenStack. OpenStack is the biggest open-source cloud computing project which has many cash-strapped tech companies constantly pushing and shoving to influence the codebase in whichever way they desire. This has caused more stagnation in OpenStack than anything else, as startups build commercial solutions to that which OpenStack does poorly, and established players try to influence the software to work well with their systems and less well with others. You can read posts from the OpenStack community, find+replace \"OpenStack\" with \"Bitcoin\" and you wouldn\'t skip a beat.\r\n\r\nBut with Bitcoin that economic factor influences almost<em>everyone</em> in the ecosystem, and there\'s a number attached to it. If things are going well, the price goes up, if things go poorly, the price goes down. Suddenly everyone is a shareholder, a speculator, a competitor, and an employee in one go.\r\n\r\nBitcoin is like a publicly listed Open Source project.\r\n\r\nThis makes it more coopetitive, where different actors in the community tend to be on the same page with wanting Bitcoin to be successful and increase in price, but have different opinions on what success means or how that should be achieved, causing endless debates and lots of fluctuation between polarized viewpoints.\r\n\r\nDistributed organisations also tend to be highly inefficient. The preferred solution to this by the Bitcoin community has been conferences. A centralised solution that inherintly restricts who gets a voice. A rather un-Bitcoin-like solution, which caused greater divide initially than creating consensus. Though it did succeed in driving out naysayers like Mike Hearne after extended debates.\r\n\r\nIf you were to try to add Bitcoin to the comic you\'d probably end up with this:\r\n<p class=\"article-image\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://markwilcox.com/content/images/2016/02/bitcoin-org-chart-2.png\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<h2 id=\"decentralisationischaos\">Decentralisation is Chaos</h2>\r\nThe really interesting dynamic that\'s new here is that the Bitcoin currency is like equity inside a highly chaotic distributed organisation - or a publicly-listed open source project, where everyone is intentivised to influence the market\'s perception of the currency.\r\n\r\nProblem is, general public market psychology favors short term profits over long term investments. So Bitcoin\'s ability to succeed depends almost entirely on its ability to weather extreme volatility. In other words: Decentralisation is Chaos, and Bitcoin gets stronger when it remains decentralised.\r\n\r\nIn the block size debate, this would argue for smaller blocks to remain the standard, if everyone was incentivised towards the price of Bitcoin increasing, which was the case until 2014. Once the price of Bitcoin stopped going up, people stopped working together and started looking at taking profit from the ecosystem as is stood. Up popped sidechains, metacurrencies, government regulation and a lot of exchanges.\r\n\r\nThis strange chaotic state of shifting incentives is likely why Bitcoin is most similar to Microsoft from the comic above. There may be many thousands of people working full time as part of the bitcoin ecosystem, but what they do in general tend to have in common across all, is that they tend to be invested in Bitcoin, and are interested in seeing the price rise over time, and generally have enough capital to continue to invest in that, rather than resort to profit-taking. The conflicting incentives then come from the \"right\" or \"wrong\" way to make Bitcoin succeed. This is similar to Microsoft in the 1990s, where there was a lot of internal conflict that balanced out the fact that everyone was getting rich together.\r\n\r\nBut contrary to Microsoft, Bitcoin isn\'t a company with strong leadership, which doesn\'t lend itself to that type of success. With no strong leadership, and with most of the apparent growth behind it, Bitcoin is a) at higher risk of going down in value and b) players in the Bitcoin ecosystem are much more likely to create value for themselves, through traditional startup founder equity and leveraging the ecosystem rather than directly contributing to it.\r\n\r\nBecause cryptocurrencies tend to be \'Public from Day One\' this is a tough challenge. No startup should ever have to weather the tolls of the public market so early in their lifetime, yet decentralised organisations based around cryptoequity sign themselves up for exactly that. This has the potential to harm new projects as well as investors.\r\n<p class=\"article-image\">For a lot of people in the Bitcoin ecosystem it\'s hard to look at an organisational growth chart like this and not feel we\'re around the middle of the chart.\r\n<img src=\"http://markwilcox.com/content/images/2016/02/bell_03-1.png\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<h2 id=\"growthofantifragilenetworks\">Growth of Antifragile Networks</h2>\r\nThe ecosystem around Bitcoin loves to think of itself as a \'Decentralised Autonomous Organisation\' but it\'s really anything but Autonomous. A better term is likely \'Decentralised Antifragile Organisation\'.\r\n\r\nIt\'s easy to look at the current state of the Bitcoin ecosystem as a disaster, but it\'s important to remember Bitcoins\' nature as an<strong> antifragile system.</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>so it\'s not so black and white</strong> While there may be lots of noise, and an extreme lack of consensus between parties in the Bitcoin ecosystem, it\'s quite unlikely that it would fork.\r\n\r\n<strong>bitcoins blockchain consensus means that this fighting is probably good as it shows that it\'s protectable</strong> This is unlikely because Bitcoin\'s network is <em>so</em> restrictive because of it\'s size and antifragile nature that, over time, it becomes harder to change, and therefore, a better store of value (not necessarily a better medium of exchange).\r\n\r\n<strong>how is it compared to competitors?</strong> What\'s important is that it\'s an anchor for alternatives. Moving in and out of different cryptocurrencies is extremely difficult without a reserve currency, and the characteristics of Bitcoin mean that it\'s going to be a relatively safe bet. Promising alternatives like <a href=\"http://ethereum.org/\">ethereum</a> are still extremely young and high risk.\r\n\r\nActor-Network Theory states that\r\n<h2 id=\"measuringgrowthinantifragiledecentralisedorganisations\">Measuring Growth in Antifragile Decentralised Organisations</h2>\r\n<strong>what is an antifragile organisation</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>an antifragile organisation should be guaranteed success</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>but it depends how the organisation defines success</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>an antifragile organisation with split consensus becomes two organisations</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>an antifragile organisation strengthens only with chaos</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>the worst thing for an antifragile organisation is silence, and no human involvement</strong> a corporate company is a good example of an organisation that seems to be antifragile in that it can survive almost anything, but it lacks efficient osmosis of noise into strength\r\n\r\n<strong>how could the community become more immune from opportunism?</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>compare to ethereum as bitcoin organisation attempt 2</strong>eth has a BDFL - vbuterin\r\n\r\n<strong>competition and monopolies</strong>','Stages of Growth and Bitcoin','','draft','closed','open','','stages-of-growth-and-bitcoin','','','2016-02-23 16:28:02','2016-02-23 16:28:02','',0,'