rrency is like equity inside a highly chaotic distributed organisation - or a publicly-listed open source project, where everyone is intentivised to influence the market\'s perception of the currency.\r\n\r\nProblem is, general public market psychology favors short term profits over long term investments. So Bitcoin\'s ability to succeed depends almost entirely on its ability to weather extreme volatility. In other words: Decentralisation is Chaos, and Bitcoin gets stronger when it remains decentralised.\r\n\r\nIn the block size debate, this would argue for smaller blocks to remain the standard, if everyone was incentivised towards the price of Bitcoin increasing, which was the case until 2014. Once the price of Bitcoin stopped going up, people stopped working together and started looking at taking profit from the ecosystem as is stood. Up popped sidechains, metacurrencies, government regulation and a lot of exchanges.\r\n\r\nThis strange chaotic state of shifting incentives is likely why Bitcoin is most similar to Microsoft from the comic above. There may be many thousands of people working full time as part of the bitcoin ecosystem, but what they do in general tend to have in common across all, is that they tend to be invested in Bitcoin, and are interested in seeing the price rise over time, and generally have enough capital to continue to invest in that, rather than resort to profit-taking. The conflicting incentives then come from the \"right\" or \"wrong\" way to make Bitcoin succeed. This is similar to Microsoft in the 1990s, where there was a lot of internal conflict that balanced out the fact that everyone was getting rich together.\r\n\r\nBut contrary to Microsoft, Bitcoin isn\'t a company with strong leadership, which doesn\'t lend itself to that type of success. With no strong leadership, and with most of the apparent growth behind it, Bitcoin is a) at higher risk of going down in value and b) players in the Bitcoin ecosystem are much more likely to create value for themselves, through traditional startup founder equity and leveraging the ecosystem rather than directly contributing to it.\r\n\r\nBecause cryptocurrencies tend to be \'Public from Day One\' this is a tough challenge. No startup should ever have to weather the tolls of the public market so early in their lifetime, yet decentralised organisations based around cryptoequity sign themselves up for exactly that. This has the potential to harm new projects as well as investors.\r\n<p class=\"article-image\">For a lot of people in the Bitcoin ecosystem it\'s hard to look at an organisational growth chart like this and not feel we\'re around the middle of the chart.\r\n<img src=\"http://markwilcox.com/content/images/2016/02/bell_03-1.png\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<h2 id=\"growthofantifragilenetworks\">Growth of Antifragile Networks</h2>\r\nThe ecosystem around Bitcoin loves to think of itself as a \'Decentralised Autonomous Organisation\' but it\'s really anything but Autonomous. A better term is likely \'Decentralised Antifragile Organisation\'.\r\n\r\nIt\'s easy to look at the current state of the Bitcoin ecosystem as a disaster, but it\'s important to remember Bitcoins\' nature as an<strong> antifragile system.</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>so it\'s not so black and white</strong> While there may be lots of noise, and an extreme lack of consensus between parties in the Bitcoin ecosystem, it\'s quite unlikely that it would fork.\r\n\r\n<strong>bitcoins blockchain consensus means that this fighting is probably good as it shows that it\'s protectable</strong> This is unlikely because Bitcoin\'s network is <em>so</em> restrictive because of it\'s size and antifragile nature that, over time, it becomes harder to change, and therefore, a better store of value (not necessarily a better medium of exchange).\r\n\r\n<strong>how is it compared to competitors?</strong> What\'s important is that it\'s an anchor for alternatives. Moving in and out of different cryptocurrencies is extremely difficult without a reserve currency, and the characteristics of Bitcoin mean that it\'s going to be a relatively safe bet. Promising alternatives like <a href=\"http://ethereum.org/\">ethereum</a> are still extremely young and high risk.\r\n\r\nActor-Network Theory states that\r\n<h2 id=\"measuringgrowthinantifragiledecentralisedorganisations\">Measuring Growth in Antifragile Decentralised Organisations</h2>\r\n<strong>what is an antifragile organisation</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>an antifragile organisation should be guaranteed success</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>but it depends how the organisation defines success</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>an antifragile organisation with split consensus becomes two organisations</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>an antifragile organisation strengthens only with chaos</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>the worst thing for an antifragile organisation is silence, and no human involvement</strong> a corporate company is a good example of an organisation that seems to be antifragile in that it can survive almost anything, but it lacks efficient osmosis of noise into strength\r\n\r\n<strong>how could the community become more immune from opportunism?</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>compare to ethereum as bitcoin organisation attempt 2</strong>eth has a BDFL - vbuterin\r\n\r\n<strong>competition and monopolies</strong>','Stages of Growth and Bitcoin','','inherit','closed','closed','','444-revision-v1','','','2016-02-23 16:26:12','2016-02-23 16:26:12','',444,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/444-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(448,17,'2016-02-24 13:52:02','2016-02-24 13:52:02','<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">There are a lot of exciting decentralization projects recently. People are aiming to turn</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> law into a programming language</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">,  make</span> <a href=\"https://bitnation.co/main/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">nation-states obsolete</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">; there even is a</span><a href=\"https://decentraland.org/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> blockchain-based virtual</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> world being planned.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">But I want to talk about a more familiar and proven decentralized app, one with a great track record of success. It was developed in 2001 and has become such a seamless part of our lives that we tend to forget how revolutionary and democratizing it really is. It accounts for a significant percentage of internet traffic, and if you\'re anything like me, it has delivered a massive amount of value to you already. The technology I am talking about is of course Bittorrent.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><img class=\" wp-image-449 alignleft\" src=\"http://magazine.backfeed.cc/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/bittorrent.png\" alt=\"bittorrent\" width=\"413\" height=\"413\" />Bittorrent allows us to exchange files, without passing them through the hands of some</span> <span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">corporation, which is what happens when you share a file or a message on Google Drive, Dropbox, Gmail, Facebook, Whatsapp or any of the hundreds of services offered by companies their like. This is a key difference. Files are passed peer-to-peer, not business-to-customer.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">This decommodifies knowledge. Instead of knowledge being provided as a business service, a free tool is given that empowers people to share. This matters. We have learned over the past few years that when you surrender control over your data, it routinely gets sold to advertisers or is handed over to police states. To surrender ownership of your data is to surrender to censors; Google can take any file down from youtube at their whim, but no one can take a file off a torrent swarm.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Political philosophy aside, there’s another major factor that should appeal to the average internet user who isn’t necessarily  a starry-eyed idealists like myself - the obvious ways in which torrents outperform their competition.</span>\r\n\r\nIf you\'ve used Bittorrent, you\'ve probably noticed that downloading this way is generally faster than downloading from most websites. There are two reasons for this: first, downloading from multiple people simultaneously is obviously quicker than downloading from one, and secondly, when there are hundreds of people serving the file, you are much more likely to find one that is geographically near to you, so the file has less distance to travel down the tubes to get to you.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">This competitive advantage is driving the next generation of peer-to-peer file delivery. Transfer speed is important because the internet is becoming more and more about video. </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Cisco projects</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> that by 2018, 4 billion people will be online, and 84% of the data we pass around will be video. That is a lot of data to be transferred, and the arithmetic suggests that the current protocols for moving content around the web won’t be able to bear that extra weight.</span>\r\n\r\nThe problem is analogous to a city with a few main roads. We already experience traffic jams. But double or triple the population, and make the vehicles heavier, and these bottlenecks get even more badly clogged. The solution is a more complex transportation system, creating a more interconnected city, where data can go from anywhere to anywhere. This will obviously unburden the main streets.\r\n\r\nThere are several proposals to apply this logic on cyberspace at large, most of which draw from the basic principles developed by bittorrent and their like.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://ipfs.io/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The Interplanetary Planetary File System</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> (IPFS) is like a next-generation Bittorrent swarm passing around videos, pictures, websites and cats. The difference between IPFS and Bittorrent is that IPFS loads files into your web browser, while combining all seeding computers to one giant distributed and decentralized server. It promises a censorship-resilient internet with the speed of a torrent swarm.</span>\r\n\r\n[embed]https://youtu.be/uypCBHLacBc[/embed]\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Storj is another decentralized platform. The first implementation competes with centralized services like Dropbox and Google Drive. When you upload a file to the Storj network, it is shredded, encrypted and sent out to a swarm of peers. No one stores your whole file, not even in an encrypted form. The advantages over storing your files on a localized server are obvious. The data on a server can be leaked, shut down, blown up, or subpoenaed. A swarm cannot. There is no gatekeeper between you and your data, unlike in Dropbox. In the future, Storj or a similar platform could replace cloud services all together.</span>\r\n\r\n[embed]https://youtu.be/vl3bUzfn2lg[/embed]\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Taking this a step forward, </span><a href=\"http://blocktech.com/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The Decentralized Library of Alexandria</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> aims to be a distributed database of all kids of media content: books, videos, etc. It aims to index files using blockchains, distribute them using IPFS, and allows for artists to be paid in Bitcoin. The idea of a distributed, uncensorable and unbreakable library for humanity\'s cultural wealth is ambitious, but inevitable. Knowledge is the most valuable thing we have, and decentralization is the safest way to store it.</span>\r\n\r\nhttps://youtu.be/zcuj_xILct0\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','The Pioneers Of Decentralized Storage','','publish','closed','open','','448-2','','','2016-02-24 13:56:56','2016-02-24 13:56:56','',0,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/?p=448',0,'post','',0),(449,8,'2016-02-24 13:29:51','2016-02-24 13:29:51','','bittorrent','','inherit','closed','closed','','bittorrent','','','2016-02-24 13:29:51','2016-02-24 13:29:51','',448,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/bittorrent.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(450,8,'2016-02-24 13:36:15','2016-02-24 13:36:15','','SplitShire-6881','','inherit','closed','closed','','splitshire-6881','','','2016-02-24 13:36:15','2016-02-24 13:36:15','',448,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/SplitShire-6881.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(451,8,'2016-02-24 13:36:24','2016-02-24 13:36:24','<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">There are a lot of exciting decentralization projects recently. People are aiming to turn</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> law into a programming language</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">,  make</span> <a href=\"https://bitnation.co/main/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">nation-states obsolete</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">; there even is a</span><a href=\"https://decentraland.org/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> blockchain-based virtual</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> world being planned.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">But I want to talk about a more familiar and proven decentralized app, one with a great track record of success. It was developed in 2001 and has become such a seamless part of our lives that we forget how revolutionary and democratizing it really is. It accounts for a significant percentage of internet traffic. If you\'re like me, it has delivered a massive amount of value to you already. The technology I am talking about is of course Bittorrent.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-449 alignleft\" src=\"http://magazine.backfeed.cc/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/bittorrent.png\" alt=\"bittorrent\" width=\"450\" height=\"450\" />Bittorrent allows us to exchange files, without passing them through the hands of some</span> <span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">corporation, which is what happens when you share a file or a message on Google Drive, Dropbox, Gmail, Facebook, Whatsapp or any of the hundreds of services offered by companies their like. This is a key difference. Files are passed peer-to-peer, not business-to-customer.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">This decommodifies knowledge. Instead of knowledge being provided as a business service, a free tool is given that empowers people to share. This matters. We have learned over the past few years that when you surrender control over your data, it routinely gets sold to advertisers or is handed over to police states. To surrender ownership of your data is to surrender to censors; Google can take any file down from youtube at their whim, but no one can take a file off a torrent swarm.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Political philosophy aside, there’s another major factor that should appeal to the average internet user who isn’t necessarily  a starry-eyed idealists like myself - the obvious ways in which torrents outperform their competition.</span>\r\n\r\nIf you\'ve used Bittorrent, you\'ve probably noticed that downloading this way is generally faster than downloading from a website. There are two reasons for this: first, downloading from multiple people simultaneously is obviously quicker than downloading from one, and secondly, when there are hundreds of people serving the file, you are much more likely to find one that is geographically near to you, so the file has less distance to travel down the tubes to get to you.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">This competitive advantage is driving the next generation of peer-to-peer file delivery. Transfer speed is important because the internet is becoming more and more about video. </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Cisco projects</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> that by 2018, 4 billion people will be online, and 84% of the data we pass around will be video. That is a lot of data to be transferred, and the arithmetic suggests that the current protocols for moving content around the web won’t be able to bear that extra weight.</span>\r\n\r\nThe problem is analogous to a city with a few main roads. We already experience traffic jams. But double or triple the population, and make the vehicles heavier, and these bottlenecks get even more badly clogged. The solution is a more complex transportation system, creating a more interconnected city, where data can go from anywhere to anywhere. This will obviously unburden the main streets.\r\n\r\nThere are several proposals to apply this logic on cyberspace at large, most of which draw from the basic principles developed by bittorrent.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://ipfs.io/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The Interplanetary Planetary File System</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> (IPFS) is like a next-generation Bittorrent swarm passing around videos, pictures, websites and cats. The difference between IPFS and Bittorrent is that IPFS loads files into your web browser, while combining all seeding computers to one giant distributed and decentralized server. It promises a censorship-resilient internet with the speed of a torrent swarm.</span>\r\n\r\n[embed]https://youtu.be/uypCBHLacBc[/embed]\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Storj is another decentralized platform. The first implementation competes with centralized services like Dropbox and Google Drive. When you upload a file to the Storj network, it is shredded, encrypted and sent out to a swarm of peers. No one stores your whole file, not even in an encrypted form. The advantages over storing your files on a localized server are obvious. The data on a server can be leaked, shut down, blown up, or subpoenaed. A swarm cannot. There is no gatekeeper between you and your data, unlike in Dropbox. In the future, Storj or a similar platform could replace cloud services all together.</span>\r\n\r\n[embed]https://youtu.be/vl3bUzfn2lg[/embed]\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Taking this a step forward, </span><a href=\"http://blocktech.com/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The Decentralized Library of Alexandria</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> aims to be a distributed database of all kids of media content: books, videos, etc. It aims to index files using blockchains, distribute them using IPFS, and allow for artists to be paid in Bitcoin. The idea of a distributed, un-take-down-able library for humanity\'s cultural wealth is ambitious, but inevitable. Knowledge is the most valuable thing we have, and decentralization is the safest way to store it.</span>\r\n\r\nhttps://youtu.be/zcuj_xILct0\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','The Pioneers Of Decentralized Storage','','inherit','closed','closed','','448-revision-v1','','','2016-02-24 13:36:24','2016-02-24 13:36:24','',448,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/448-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(452,8,'2016-02-24 13:43:44','2016-02-24 13:43:44','<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">There are a lot of exciting decentralization projects recently. People are aiming to turn</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> law into a programming language</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">,  make</span> <a href=\"https://bitnation.co/main/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">nation-states obsolete</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">; there even is a</span><a href=\"https://decentraland.org/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> blockchain-based virtual</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> world being planned.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">But I want to talk about a more familiar and proven decentralized app, one with a great track record of success. It was developed in 2001 and has become such a seamless part of our lives that we tend to forget how revolutionary and democratizing it really is. It accounts for a significant percentage of internet traffic, and if you\'re anything like me, it has delivered a massive amount of value to you already. The technology I am talking about is of course Bittorrent.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-449 alignleft\" src=\"http://magazine.backfeed.cc/wp-content/uploads/2016/02/bittorrent.png\" alt=\"bittorrent\" width=\"450\" height=\"450\" />Bittorrent allows us to exchange files, without passing them through the hands of some</span> <span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">corporation, which is what happens when you share a file or a message on Google Drive, Dropbox, Gmail, Facebook, Whatsapp or any of the hundreds of services offered by companies their like. This is a key difference. Files are passed peer-to-peer, not business-to-customer.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">This decommodifies knowledge. Instead of knowledge being provided as a business service, a free tool is given that empowers people to share. This matters. We have learned over the past few years that when you surrender control over your data, it routinely gets sold to advertisers or is handed over to police states. To surrender ownership of your data is to surrender to censors; Google can take any file down from youtube at their whim, but no one can take a file off a torrent swarm.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Political philosophy aside, there’s another major factor that should appeal to the average internet user who isn’t necessarily  a starry-eyed idealists like myself - the obvious ways in which torrents outperform their competition.</span>\r\n\r\nIf you\'ve used Bittorrent, you\'ve probably noticed that downloading this way is generally faster than downloading from most websites. There are two reasons for this: first, downloading from multiple people simultaneously is obviously quicker than downloading from one, and secondly, when there are hundreds of people serving the file, you are much more likely to find one that is geographically near to you, so the file has less distance to travel down the tubes to get to you.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">This competitive advantage is driving the next generation of peer-to-peer file delivery. Transfer speed is important because the internet is becoming more and more about video. </span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Cisco projects</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> that by 2018, 4 billion people will be online, and 84% of the data we pass around will be video. That is a lot of data to be transferred, and the arithmetic suggests that the current protocols for moving content around the web won’t be able to bear that extra weight.</span>\r\n\r\nThe problem is analogous to a city with a few main roads. We already experience traffic jams. But double or triple the population, and make the vehicles heavier, and these bottlenecks get even more badly clogged. The solution is a more complex transportation system, creating a more interconnected city, where data can go from anywhere to anywhere. This will obviously unburden the main streets.\r\n\r\nThere are several proposals to apply this logic on cyberspace at large, most of which draw from the basic principles developed by bittorrent and their like.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://ipfs.io/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The Interplanetary Planetary File System</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> (IPFS) is like a next-generation Bittorrent swarm passing around videos, pictures, websites and cats. The difference between IPFS and Bittorrent is that IPFS loads files into your web browser, while combining all seeding computers to one giant distributed and decentralized server. It promises a censorship-resilient internet with the speed of a torrent swarm.</span>\r\n\r\n[embed]https://youtu.be/uypCBHLacBc[/embed]\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Storj is another decentralized platform. The first implementation competes with centralized services like Dropbox and Google Drive. When you upload a file to the Storj network, it is shredded, encrypted and sent out to a swarm of peers. No one stores your whole file, not even in an encrypted form. The advantages over storing your files on a localized server are obvious. The data on a server can be leaked, shut down, blown up, or subpoenaed. A swarm cannot. There is no gatekeeper between you and your data, unlike in Dropbox. In the future, Storj or a similar platform could replace cloud services all together.</span>\r\n\r\n[embed]https://youtu.be/vl3bUzfn2lg[/embed]\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Taking this a step forward, </span><a href=\"http://blocktech.com/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The Decentralized Library of Alexandria</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> aims to be a distributed database of all kids of media content: books, videos, etc. It aims to index files using blockchains, distribute them using IPFS, and allow for artists to be paid in Bitcoin. The idea of a distributed, un-take-down-able library for humanity\'s cultural wealth is ambitious, but inevitable. Knowledge is the most valuable thing we have, and decentralization is the safest way to store it.</span>\r\n\r\nhttps://youtu.be/zcuj_xILct0\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','The Pioneers Of Decentralized Storage','','inherit','closed','closed','','448-revision-v1','','','2016-02-24 13:43:44','2016-02-24 13:43:44','',448,'http://magazine.backfeed.cc/448-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(453,8,'2016-02-24 13:51:26','2016-02-24 13:51:26','<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">There are a lot of exciting decentralization projects recently. People are aiming to turn</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> law into a programming language</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">,  make</span> <a href=\"https://bitnation.co/main/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">nation-states obsolete</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">; there even is a</span><a href=\"https://decentraland.org/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> blockchain-based virtual</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\